"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506627","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Immigration Skills Charge will be paid by UK employers recruiting skilled migrant labour from outside the European Economic Area. This includes employers of nurses. The charge will apply from April 2017. There will be a flat rate of £1,000 per Tier 2 migrant sponsored per year. Some public sector employers could benefit from the small and charitable sponsors reduced rate of £364 per Tier 2 migrant sponsored per year.</p><p>As the independent Migration Advisory Committee stated in their January 2016 report on Tier 2, public sector organisations are employers like any other and should be incentivised to consider the UK labour market first, before recruiting outside Europe.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-18T15:11:41.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506627/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506627/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Nurses: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he plans for the proposed £1,000 immigration skills charge to apply to NHS nurses.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","32688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506628","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Home Office does not disclose country specific information regarding deportation of foreign national offenders in any public material, including Freedom of Information Requests, as its disclosure could prejudice relations between the UK and foreign governments. Parliamentary Questions are approached in the same way.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-19T14:39:53.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506628/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506628/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people of each nationality are awaiting deportation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","32683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506629","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>Holders of Latvian non-citizen status are not considered to be European Economic Area (EEA) nationals for the purposes of immigration policy.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-18T14:24:39.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506629/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506629/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","EEA Nationals: Latvia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether holders of Latvian non-citizen status are considered to be EEA nationals for the purposes of immigration policy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","32738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506630","Home Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>In the last three years, over 13,000 family reunion visas have been granted under the Immigration Rules. This information is available in the quarterly statistics published by the Home Office and available on Gov.UK here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015/list-of-tables#visas</p><p>A further 65 visas have been granted outside the Rules due to exceptional circumstances.</p><p>We have committed to making clearer in revised guidance the kinds of cases which may benefit from leave outside the Immigration Rules due to exceptional circumstances. The guidance will be updated by the end of April.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-13T16:01:43.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506630/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506630/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answers of 15 March 2016 to Questions 30647 and 30649, what the evidential basis is for the statement that her Department's policy enables thousands of people each year to be reunited with their families in the UK; and how many extended family members seeking family reunion have been granted asylum in exceptional circumstances by the Entry Clearance Officer in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","32719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506631","Home Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>In order to ensure that special constables have legal protection, the Home Office provides legal assistance cover currently through Arc Legal Assistance. This is available to all special constables, free of charge, and includes personal injury cover including financial compensation for damages. It also includes cover for legal advice as well as representation at criminal proceedings.</p><p>The Government recognise the importance of police welfare. In October 2014 we allocated £10 million to help support emergency services personnel and volunteers, focused on mental health, physical recuperation and bereavement support for those who need it.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-13T09:16:53.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506631/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506631/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Special Constables: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what insurance cover her Department and police forces make available for special constables who are injured on duty and require long-term compensation for loss of earnings.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","32724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506632","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>Data on the number of outstanding decisions and cases awaiting appeal is published as part of the Government’s Transparency Agenda. Further information can be found via the link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asylum-transparency-data-february-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asylum-transparency-data-february-2016</a></p><p>As of the end of December 2015 there were 18,060 cases awaiting an initial decision with 10,193 cases having lodged an appeal and awaiting either a first hearing or further appeal hearing dates.</p><p>We aim to decide all straightforward asylum claims within 6 months, however there will be some claims which are complex. We aim to decide these cases within 12 months.</p><p>This data relates to asylum claims submitted post October 2006 and includes asylum cases which are still awaiting the results of their asylum claim, where no initial decision has been made. It also includes asylum cases awaiting the results of their asylum appeal, where the claimant has lodged a first appeal and it has not been heard, as well as cases where the claimant has lodged an appeal and it has not been decided. Therefore these asylum cases have not exhausted their appeal rights.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-18T13:13:37.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506632/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506632/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people are currently awaiting the results of asylum (a) claims and (b) appeals.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","32992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506633","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>Immigration appeals are determined by the First-tier Tribunal (Immigration and Asylum Chamber) and Upper Tribunal (Immigration and Asylum Chamber) which are administered by HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS).</p><p> </p><p>HMCTS works with the Home Office and others to monitor and continuously improve appeal processes and timeliness.</p><p> </p><p>The Immigration Act 2014 simplified the appeals system, reducing the number of decisions that can be appealed. For the quarter October to December 2015, 18,368 appeals were received – a 29% reduction when compared with the same quarter in 2014.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-18T12:01:15.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506633/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506633/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to (a) shorten the immigration appeals process and (b) reduce the number of immigration appeals.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","32993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506634","Home Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>No central records are kept of (i) the number of judicial reviews initiated against the department since 2010; (ii) the cost of defending such challenges; or (iii) the number of such challenges which have been successful. It would incur disproportionate cost to try to acquire this information.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","33213","2016-04-13T16:09:18.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506634/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506634/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Home Office: Judicial Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many judicial reviews against her Department have (a) been initiated and (b) were successful since 2010.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","32996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506635","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>Published statistics detailing the total number of appeals disposed of by the tribunals, and the percentage of these which have been allowed and dismissed by the First-tier Tribunal from 2007/08 and the Upper Tribunal from 2010/11, can be viewed on the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-and-gender-recognition-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-and-gender-recognition-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-18T12:05:26.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506635/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506635/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of immigration appeals have been successful in each year since 2004.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","32995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506636","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>Up until January 1st 2016 the Assisted Voluntary Return (AVR) scheme has been outsourced but is now part of the Home Office Voluntary Return Service (VRS).</p><p>The cost of the outsourced scheme in the years 2006 to 2015 is set out below. Data for 2004 to 2006 is incomplete and has therefore been omitted.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-7</p></td><td><p>22.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-8</p></td><td><p>21.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>10.80</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>20.40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>17.30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>7.50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>8.77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>8.84</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>10.86</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-18T15:55:36.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506636/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506636/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Assisted Voluntary Return Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost to the public purse of the assisted voluntary return scheme was in each year since 2004.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","32994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506637","Home Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>UK Visas and Immigration caseworkers were issued with guidance on how to handle applications made by international students who had taken ETS English language tests in February 2014. This guidance has been updated as required. This is part of the reasonable and proportionate action we have taken in response to the clear evidence provided by ETS to identify those who had sought to profit from abuse of the English language testing system. The guidance does not disadvantage students who obtained an ETS test certificate properly, but ensures that due scrutiny is being applied by caseworkers where individuals have been identified as having obtained invalid test certificates.</p><p>We received the determination in the case of Qadir and SM from the Upper Tribunal on 8 April, providing full reasons for the summary decision handed down on 23 March. Although the Upper Tribunal found that the Home Office did discharge the evidential burden on it in establishing fraud at ETS test centres and that each appellant would need to establish an innocent explanation, it went on to allow the appeals. We are disappointed by the decision and we are currently reviewing it with a view to challenging before the Court of Appeal. Given this, there are no current plans to issue further updated guidance to caseworkers following the recent Upper Tribunal determination.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-14T14:55:31.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506637/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506637/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506637/answer/previousversion/54800","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Overseas Students: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department has issued to caseworkers on handling applications from international students to study at UK colleges and universities in a way that ensures the applicants are not disadvantaged by accusation of fraud in English language tests made by ETS.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","33039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506638","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-18T14:30:07.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506638/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506638/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Immigration Controls: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 31 March 2016 to Question 31313, on immigration controls: EU nationals, whether any of the people refused entry have subsequently been permitted to enter the UK.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","33005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506639","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>Removals have been increasing year on year since 2010. In 2015, we removed 5,602 FNOs and over 29,000 foreign national offenders have been removed since 2010.</p><p>Our records indicate that as of December 2015, there were 4,217 EEA foreign national offenders awaiting deportation.</p><p>Of which:</p><p>2,748 are still serving a custodial sentence</p><p>A total of 302 are time served detained in immigration removal centres (IRC) and prisons. (242 in IRCs and 60 in prison)</p><p>1,167 are living in the community.</p><p>Of the above, for those detained and living in the community (1,469), the time since the end of their custodial sentence is as follows:</p><p>Less than one month 50</p><p>One to three months 84</p><p>Three to six months 58</p><p>Six to nine months 60</p><p>Nine to 12 months 49</p><p>One to two years 132</p><p>More than two years 80</p><p>No UK conviction or sentence end date not recorded 956</p><p>Total 1,469</p><p>(1) The figures quoted have been derived from management information from the Home Office databases and are therefore provisional and subject to change. This information has not been quality assured under National Statistics protocols.</p><p>(2) FNOs living in the community include those released by an Immigration Judge, those released by the Secretary of State and those with oversees convictions who may not have received a custodial sentence in the UK.</p><p>(3) The data provided is up to December 2015. This is not routinely published data. General protocol is that the figures should not breach the National Statistics, so we are not able to disclose figures that are for a later period than those that we have published. Published figures are available up to 31 December 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","33099","2016-04-21T14:49:35.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506639/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506639/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Deportation: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2016 to Question 31329, on deportation: EU nationals, how many EEA foreign national offenders awaiting deportation have been waiting (a) less than one month, (b) one to three months, (c) three to six months, (d) six to nine months, (e) nine to 12 months, (f) one to two years and (g) more than two years.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","33096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506640","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Home Office does not disclose country specific information regarding deportation of foreign national offenders in any public material, including Freedom of Information Requests, as its disclosure could prejudice relations between the UK and foreign governments. Parliamentary Questions are approached in the same way.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-19T13:29:25.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506640/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506640/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Deportation: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2016 to Question 31329, on deportation: EU nationals, what the nationality is of the EEA foreign national offenders awaiting deportation.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","33097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506641","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>Removals have been increasing year on year since 2010. In 2015, we removed 5,602 FNOs and over 29,000 foreign national offenders have been removed since 2010.</p><p>Our records indicate that as of December 2015, there were 4,217 EEA foreign national offenders awaiting deportation.</p><p>Of which:</p><p>2,748 are still serving a custodial sentence</p><p>A total of 302 are time served detained in immigration removal centres (IRC) and prisons. (242 in IRCs and 60 in prison)</p><p>1,167 are living in the community.</p><p>Of the above, for those detained and living in the community (1,469), the time since the end of their custodial sentence is as follows:</p><p>Less than one month 50</p><p>One to three months 84</p><p>Three to six months 58</p><p>Six to nine months 60</p><p>Nine to 12 months 49</p><p>One to two years 132</p><p>More than two years 80</p><p>No UK conviction or sentence end date not recorded 956</p><p>Total 1,469</p><p>(1) The figures quoted have been derived from management information from the Home Office databases and are therefore provisional and subject to change. This information has not been quality assured under National Statistics protocols.</p><p>(2) FNOs living in the community include those released by an Immigration Judge, those released by the Secretary of State and those with oversees convictions who may not have received a custodial sentence in the UK.</p><p>(3) The data provided is up to December 2015. This is not routinely published data. General protocol is that the figures should not breach the National Statistics, so we are not able to disclose figures that are for a later period than those that we have published. Published figures are available up to 31 December 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","33096","2016-04-21T14:49:36.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506641/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506641/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Deportation: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2016 to Question 31329, on deportation: EU nationals, how many of the EEA foreign national offenders awaiting deportation are (a) in immigration removal centres, (b) in custody or other form of detention, (c) on bail and (d) living in the community.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","33099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506642","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>Removals have been increasing year on year since 2010. In 2015, we removed 5,602 FNOs and over 29,000 foreign national offenders have been removed since 2010. Our records indicate that as of December 2015, there were 4,217 EEA foreign national offenders awaiting deportation.</p><p>Please find table below with the number of EEA foreign national offenders who were awaiting deportation in December since 2010.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Dec-10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec 13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec 14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec 15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total EEA FNO Stock</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,715</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,955</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,130</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,212</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,795</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4,217</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>(1) The figures quoted have been derived from management information from the Home Office databases and are therefore provisional and subject to change. This information has not been quality assured under National Statistics protocols.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(2) The data provided is up to December 2015. This is not routinely published data. General protocol is that the figures should not breach the National Statistics, so we are not able to disclose figures that are for a later period than those that we have published. Published figures are available up to 31 December 2015. (3) A Foreign National Offender (FNO) is defined as an individual with a criminal case on the Home Office's Case Information Database (CID) and may include individuals with asylum cases. (4) Due to changes in reporting, comparable data is not available prior to 2010. (5) EEA national figures inclusive of Irish nationals.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-21T14:49:57.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506642/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506642/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Deportation: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2016 to Question 31329, on deportation: EU nationals, how many EEA foreign national offenders were awaiting deportation in December of each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","33098"
