"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506663","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government has no current plans to revise the existing Equality Act exemptions relating to language analysis testing.</p><p>No further nationalities have been added to the Equality Act exemption authorisation since it was introduced in 2013.</p><p>A review on language analysis use was undertaken in 2011 and published in 2012.</p><p>(https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/257177/language-analysis.pdf).</p><p>No further such review is presently planned. However, we do monitor the use of language analysis regularly to ensure it is used as effectively as possible and to identify new trends in nationality swapping.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","33138 ; 33195","2016-04-18T14:29:06.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506663/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506663/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Asylum: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Equality (Language Analysis - Palestinian, Syrian and Kuwaiti Testing) Authorisation (No. 2) 2013, whether the Government plans to revise the existing three exceptions.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","33137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506664","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government has no current plans to revise the existing Equality Act exemptions relating to language analysis testing.</p><p>No further nationalities have been added to the Equality Act exemption authorisation since it was introduced in 2013.</p><p>A review on language analysis use was undertaken in 2011 and published in 2012.</p><p>(https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/257177/language-analysis.pdf).</p><p>No further such review is presently planned. However, we do monitor the use of language analysis regularly to ensure it is used as effectively as possible and to identify new trends in nationality swapping.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","33137 ; 33195","2016-04-18T14:29:06.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506664/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506664/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-08","Asylum: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Equality (Language Analysis - Palestinian, Syrian and Kuwaiti Testing) Authorisation (No. 2) 2013, whether any further nationalities have been added to the list of exceptions.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","33138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506665","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-13","<p>The UK is the 4<sup>th</sup> largest donor to the crisis in Yemen and has more than doubled its humanitarian support over the last year to £85 million for 2015/16. We have so far helped more than 1.3 million Yemenis who have been affected by the conflict with food assistance, medical supplies, water, and emergency shelter, as well as supporting refugees and migrants in Yemen. We work through International Non-Governmental Organisations and United Nations agencies to deliver this assistance, ensuring the response is targeted towards the most vulnerable.</p><p> </p><p>This funding includes support to the UN Children’s Fund (UNICEF) to provide over 750,000 Internally Displaced People and people affected by the conflict with access to a safe water supply and critical hygiene items. The UK has also provided funds to the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), UNICEF and Save the Children to raise awareness of child rights, to monitor and support displaced children and to provide children with food, nutritional support, water and sanitation.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-13T13:35:24.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506665/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506665/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Yemen: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the provision of medical supplies, water, food and emergency shelter for internally displaced people and children in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","33128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506666","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-13","<p>DFID’s Agricultural Policy Framework, published last year, sets out the approach and steps DFID will take to support agriculture. Depending on context and need, this is expected to include support to small scale organic, or smallholder, farmers in Africa<strong>. </strong>Our priorities include helping smallholder farmers to increase their productivity, and to better link them to markets to sell their produce so as to increase their incomes, improve their livelihoods and contribute to economic growth and poverty reduction.</p><p> </p><p>For example we are providing support to the International Fund Agriculture Development’s Adaptation for Smallholder Agriculture Programme. This will help smallholder farmers in Africa cope with the impacts of climate change by providing extension services to farmers, improving irrigation and infrastructure, and helping farmers to increase their harvests through improved seeds and better soil and land management practices.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-13T13:24:33.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506666/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506666/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Africa: Organic Farming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is taking steps to ensure that UK aid spent in Africa supports small-scale organic farmers.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","33051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506667","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>Much of our assistance is already laying the groundwork for future reconciliation, stabilisation and reconstruction efforts inside Syria. Regarding the economy, we are already taking a long term approach to foster market stability and economic recovery. This includes the supply of agricultural inputs to farmers to increase production as well as support to small businesses. This has potential to be scaled up once a political transition is reached and depending on the nature of that settlement.</p><p> </p><p>On 26 November 2015, the Prime Minister announced that the UK will commit at least £1 billion to Syria’s reconstruction. We anticipate that reconstruction funds would be allocated against a plan agreed between a new, inclusive Syrian government and the international community. We expect that, over time, this funding will include support for re-building Syria’s shattered economy and infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p>However, we must not underestimate the scale of the challenge of post-conflict reconstruction. Syria has experienced 40 years under an oppressive regime and a brutal civil war. Conflict has reversed Syria into poverty. Consequently, reconstruction will cost hundreds of billions of dollars. That is why we will use our influence as a major shareholder to push the UN and International Financial Institutions and the private sector to bring their planning, resources and expertise to bear.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:16:32.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506667/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506667/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Syria: Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to support Syria's economy after the end of the current conflict in that country.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","33094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506668","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>The UK supports efforts to improve tax transparency. We initiated international work on country-by-country (CbC) reporting during our G8 Presidency in 2013, calling on the OECD to develop a framework for CbC reporting to tax authorities as part of the Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) project. This important initiative will enhance transparency between business and tax authorities, including those of developing countries.</p><p> </p><p>DFID funds the Global Forum and the World Bank to provide technical assistance to improve exchange of tax information in developing countries which will allow tax authorities to gain access to information such as country-by-country reports. We also support the OECD in helping developing countries tackle multinational practices such as transfer pricing and have provided HMRC tax auditors to Tax Inspectors Without Borders, which puts expert tax auditors in the field working on complex multinational audit cases.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","33170","2016-04-15T10:18:31.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506668/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506668/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Developing Countries: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of public country-by-country reporting of corporation tax details by multinational companies on the economies of developing countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","33169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506669","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>The UK supports efforts to improve tax transparency. We initiated international work on country-by-country (CbC) reporting during our G8 Presidency in 2013, calling on the OECD to develop a framework for CbC reporting to tax authorities as part of the Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) project. This important initiative will enhance transparency between business and tax authorities, including those of developing countries.</p><p> </p><p>DFID funds the Global Forum and the World Bank to provide technical assistance to improve exchange of tax information in developing countries which will allow tax authorities to gain access to information such as country-by-country reports. We also support the OECD in helping developing countries tackle multinational practices such as transfer pricing and have provided HMRC tax auditors to Tax Inspectors Without Borders, which puts expert tax auditors in the field working on complex multinational audit cases.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","33169","2016-04-15T10:18:31.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506669/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506669/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Developing Countries: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department plans to take to ensure that public country-by-country reporting of corporation tax benefits developing countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","33170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506670","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>The £650 million reduction to the ODA budget will be from DFID’s baseline budget. DFID’s baseline budget includes transfers to other government departments and funds. Decisions on the allocation of reductions will be taken on the basis of the impact of expenditure and strategic fit with government objectives.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:23:28.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506670/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506670/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to paragraph 1.59 of the Budget 2016, from which projects and programmes the £650 million reduction in Official Development Assistance will come.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","32939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506671","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>No UK aid is used for payments to Palestinian prisoners, or their families. The UK’s direct financial assistance to the PA is used to pay the salaries of public sector workers only. Our support is provided through a multi-donor trust fund administered by the World Bank, which carries out close monitoring of Palestinian Authority expenditure. Only named civil servants from a pre-approved EU list are eligible. The process is subject to independent auditing.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:24:52.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506671/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506671/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that UK Government aid to the Palestinian Territories is not used to help finance violence or terrorism.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","32922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506672","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>The Central African Republic (CAR) has faced a severe and protracted crisis since 2012. 900,000 people (20% of the population) are still internally displaced or refugees in neighbouring countries. Needs remain high.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has provided £58m since 2013 to give CAR populations and CAR refugees access to essential humanitarian assistance, including livelihoods support. DFID is currently undertaking aid reviews, which will set out business plans for Africa humanitarian support.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-15T12:41:59.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506672/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506672/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Central African Republic: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department plans to provide for humanitarian assistance in the Central African Republic in the 2016-17 financial year.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","32884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506673","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>UK direct financial assistance to the Palestinian Authority (PA) is used to pay the salaries of civil servant and pensioners. Our support is provided through a multi-donor trust fund administered by the World Bank, which carries out close monitoring of PA expenditure. Only named civil servants from a pre-approved European Union list are eligible, and the vetting process ensures that our funds do not benefit terrorist groups. The process is subject to independent auditing.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:25:49.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506673/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506673/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what mechanisms for oversight her Department has for UK Government aid to the Palestinian Authority.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","32923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506674","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>At the London Conference, the Prime Minister announced that the UK will more than double our total pledge to the Syria crisis from £1.12 billion to over £2.3 billion. The UK has already spent more than £1.1 billion in providing lifesaving aid in Syria and the region.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:27:41.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506674/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506674/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Syria: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the Supporting Syria Conference 2016, to whom and by what mechanisms the Government's funding pledges at that conference will be made.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","33095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506675","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>Sustainable economic development in South Sudan will require peace and political will from the country’s leaders. This means appointing a transitional government of national unity as soon as possible and implementing the peace agreement signed in August 2015. The UK remains committed to the people of South Sudan. DFID supports livelihoods and basic services for the people of South Sudan alongside life-saving humanitarian support. We support economic development by helping to improve the capacity of key institutions, and through our support to improving the effectiveness and transparency of customs operations. DFID has no plans to support the development of oil and mineral production beyond seeking to ensure a greater degree of transparency in the sector.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-15T12:43:25.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506675/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506675/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","South Sudan: Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to encourage (a) development of oil and mineral production and (b) other economic development within South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","33073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506676","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-14","<p>The UK government will be represented at the UN General Assembly high-level meeting on ending AIDS at the UN headquarters in New York in June 2016. Precise attendance has still to be finalised.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-14T16:03:35.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506676/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506676/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which (a) Ministers and (b) officials of her Department plan to attend the UN General Assembly high-level meeting on HIV/AIDS at the UN headquarters in New York in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","32740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506678","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>The UK has contributed £36.2 million to the Yemen Emergency Response Fund (ERF) since it was established in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015 the ERF channelled funds to over 79 projects implemented by UN agencies and national and international NGOs. Through the total resources received from donors in 2015, the Fund has provided critical life-saving assistance to 3.3 million people affected by the conflict in Yemen, including through the provision of healthcare, clean water, sanitation services, food supplies or shelter materials.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:17:24.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506678/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506678/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the UK contribution has been to the UN's emergency relief fund for Yemen since its creation.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","32680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506679","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-13","<p>The most effective way for DFID to have a sustainable impact on dengue fever and other vector-borne diseases is through our support to vector control, which is very important to protect populations from dengue and other vector borne diseases. Our partners include the Innovative Vector Control Consortium based at the Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine, which is a product development partnership that brings together partners from the public and private sectors to develop new insecticides that can be used to control insects that spread this disease.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-13T13:20:43.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506679/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506679/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Developing Countries: Dengue Fever","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department has provided to tackle dengue fever.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","32828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506680","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-15","<p>The UK is the 4<sup>th</sup> largest donor to the crisis in Yemen and has more than doubled its humanitarian support over the last year to £85 million for 2015/16. We have so far helped more than 1.3 million Yemenis who have been affected by the conflict with food assistance, medical supplies, water, and emergency shelter, as well as supporting refugees and migrants in Yemen.</p><p> </p><p>We work through International Non-Governmental Organisations and the United Nations agencies, including the World Food Programme who provide emergency food to over 570,000 people, either through direct delivery of food or providing cash or vouchers to enable people to buy food. These distributions are prioritised to the areas of greatest need. We are also funding the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism to improve the supply of essential commercial goods, including food, into Yemen.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-15T10:19:37.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506680/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506680/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what measures she is taking to assist humanitarian agencies in distributing food and supplies to people affected by the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","32786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506681","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-13","<p>Ministers and officials meet regularly with the Word Health Organisation to discuss a range of health issues including on the management of disease outbreaks. Dengue was discussed during last year’s World Health Assembly (WHA), which brings together the member states to discuss important issues. Senior officials from DFID and the Department of Health participate at the WHA.</p><p> </p><p>DFID's health focus is to improve the provision of basic health services for the poorest by supporting health systems strengthening, health worker capacity and access to essential medicines and equipment. Increasing coverage, access and quality will strengthen health services to address all health problems including communicable diseases.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-13T13:25:21.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506681/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506681/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Developing Countries: Dengue Fever","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her foreign counterparts on efforts to tackle dengue fever.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","32829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506682","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-13","<p>Dengue is estimated to place a heavy socio-economic burden on households, health care systems and governments, particularly during outbreaks; however, country-specific reliable estimates of burden of disease and cost data are limited.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-13T13:25:59.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506682/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506682/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Developing Countries: Dengue Fever","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of dengue fever on the development of developing countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","32830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506683","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-13","<p>In the last three years the Ethical Trading Initiative (ETI) has received £1.2m in funding from DFID, through a Programme Partnership Arrangement (PPA). PPA funding supports ETI to improve working conditions for poor and vulnerable people, this includes workers in top tier farms and factories, as well as those in the lower tiers of supply chains (such as women homeworkers, smallholders and migrant workers) who are harder to reach and more vulnerable to exploitation. PPA funding is not tied to specific initiatives or interventions but ETI are expected to meet objectives set out in a robust performance framework, agreed between DFID and ETI.</p><p> </p><p>PPA funding was based on competitive selection and open to organisations who were regarded as leaders in their field and who could deliver on DFID’s objectives. Organisations were selected following a rigorous assessment and quality assurance process.</p><p> </p><p>Freedom of Association and collective bargaining is a component of the ETI Base Code and therefore every ETI member commits to taking action to support this right.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-13T13:36:36.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506683/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506683/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-08","Ethical Trading Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding the Ethical Trading Initiative (ETI) received from the Government in the last three years; for what reasons that funding is provided; against what criteria the decision to fund that organisation was made; and what obligations the ETI places on its member companies with respect to freedom of association and collective bargaining.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","33184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506684","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-13","<p>The decision to be an organ donor is for prisoners to discuss with their next of kin and to decide whether they wish to add their name to the National Organ Donor Register. Organ donation by prisoners who are transferred to hospital prior to death may be considered in certain clinical circumstances and providing that it does not affect any coroner investigation.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-13T10:42:52.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506684/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506684/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Prisoners: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether prisons record whether inmates are registered as organ donors; and what protocols are in place for donation of organs after a death in custody.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","33183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506685","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>Prison Officers employed in the Scottish Prison Service are members of the Civil Service. All members of the Principal Civil Service Pension Scheme (PCSPS) who transitioned into the Civil Service (and Others) Pension Scheme (CSOPS, also known as alpha) were notified by letter to inform them of the change, in accordance with the Occupational and Personal Pension Schemes (Disclosure of Information) Regulations. In addition, relevant Employers were provided with a variety of communication products to inform their staff and support those who needed to make decisions. These were also held on the Civil Service Pensions website.</p><p>Between 2011 and 2015 Cabinet Office Ministers and officials held extensive discussions with all of the Civil Service unions, including the Prison Officers’ Association, on the detail of the pension reforms. There was also discussion with both the Scottish Prison Service and National Offender Management Service on the detail of the pension offer to operational staff in Prisons.</p><p>The Civil Service is a Reserved Matter and this includes pensions for all Civil Servants. Representations on the pension age of Scottish Prison Officers were made to me by the Scottish Cabinet Secretary for Justice in July last year. I replied later that month.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","33236","2016-04-19T08:44:05.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506685/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506685/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-08","Prison Officers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what consultations his Department had with (a) the Scottish Prison Service, (b) Scottish Ministers and (c) the Prison Officers Association on the transfer of Prison Officers' Pensions from Classic to the Alpha Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","33240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506686","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-19","<p>There was no written or other contact between any Ministry of Justice Minister and senior executives at (a) AXA UK, (b) Ageas UK, (c) General Insurance, (d) Direct Line Insurance and (e) Admiral Insurance between 1 September and 26 November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Details of all Ministerial meetings are included in transparency returns which are published quarterly on gov.uk at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/moj-data-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings-returns-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/moj-data-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings-returns-october-to-december-2015</a>.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-04-19T12:07:24.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506686/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506686/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Ministry of Justice: Insurance Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what (a) written and (b) other contacts he or Ministers in his Department had with senior executives at (a) AXA UK, (b) Ageas UK, (c) General Insurance, (d) Direct Line Insurance and (e) Admiral Insurance between 1 September and 26 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","32803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506687","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service does not hold the requested information centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-14T15:22:26.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506687/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506687/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","HM Courts and Tribunals Service: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many medically qualified panel members of HM Courts and Tribunals services in the North East of England are orthopaedic specialists.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506688","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates courts and found guilty at all courts specifically of offences under article 222 of the Air Navigation Order 2009, with the conviction ratio, in England and Wales, from 2010 to 2014 (the latest available) can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="8"><p><strong>Defendants proceeded against at magistrates courts and found guilty at all courts of offences under S222 Air Navigation Order 2009, England and Wales, 2010 to 2014 <sup>(1)(2)</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Statute</p></td><td><p>Offence</p></td><td><p>Outcome</p></td><td><p>2010 <sup>(3)</sup></p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p>Air Navigation Order 2009, AA.221(a) &amp; (b), 222 &amp; 241(5) &amp; Sch 13 Part B</p></td><td rowspan="3"><p>Exhibiting, directing or shining a light which by its glare or liability to be mistaken for an aeronautical ground light would endanger aircraft</p></td><td><p>Proceeded against</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>54</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Found guilty</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>19</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Conviction ratio <sup>(4)</sup></p></td><td><p>87%</p></td><td><p>87%</p></td><td><p>73%</p></td><td><p>91%</p></td><td><p>90%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="8"><p>(1) The figures given in the table on court proceedings relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="8"><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(3) Data for 2010 includes other offences related to lasers which cannot be separately analysed.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>(4) The conviction ratio is calculated as the number of convictions as a proportion of the number of proceedings.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Ref: PQ 32959</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-18T11:32:45.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506688/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506688/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Aviation: Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2016 to Question 30119, on aviation: lasers, what proportion of those cases ended in prosecution in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506689","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The number of offenders found guilty at all courts of offences under the Gangmasters Licensing Act 2004, in England and Wales, from 2004 to 2014 (the latest available) can be viewed at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.gla.gov.uk/our-impact/conviction-totals/" target="_blank">http://www.gla.gov.uk/our-impact/conviction-totals/</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-18T15:19:06.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506689/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506689/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Gangmasters (Licensing) Act 2004: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many convictions have been secured under the Gangmasters (Licensing) Act since its introduction in 2004.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","32919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506690","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-19","<p>The government remains concerned about the number and cost of whiplash claims which are out of all proportion to any genuine injury suffered. The Autumn Statement referred to the cost to society of the substantial industry that encourages claims through cold calling and other social nuisances and which increases premiums for consumers.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-04-19T12:11:45.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506690/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506690/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraph 1.143 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, how the Government defines the term claims culture.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","32687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506691","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Criminal Inquiries Compensation Scheme is administered by the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority. The Authority does not record or collect data on the nationality of individuals who make applications for compensation or are granted awards of compensation under the Scheme.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-18T11:26:31.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506691/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506691/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Crimes of Violence: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many nationals of other EU member states who have been victims of violent crime in the UK have been compensated as a result of EU legislation in each year since 2010; and how much that compensation amounted to.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","32690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506692","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>Driving offences can have devastating consequences for victims and their loved ones.</p><p> </p><p>The government is aware of concerns about a number of sentencing issues and is committed to making sure sentencing for driving crimes is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework. It is our intention to commence a consultation in due course which will look at driving offences and penalties.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","32667","2016-04-14T14:51:48.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506692/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506692/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Road Traffic Offences: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department's review of criminal driving offences will consider changes to the distinction between careless and dangerous driving offences.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","32666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506693","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>Driving offences can have devastating consequences for victims and their loved ones.</p><p> </p><p>The government is aware of concerns about a number of sentencing issues and is committed to making sure sentencing for driving crimes is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework. It is our intention to commence a consultation in due course which will look at driving offences and penalties.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","32666","2016-04-14T14:51:48.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506693/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506693/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Road Traffic Offences: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the terms of reference of his Department's review of criminal driving offences.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","32667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506694","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Alpha pension, which introduced a higher Normal Pension Age, was brought in under legislation. All consultation/negotiations with the Civil Service trade unions including the Prison Officers Association (POA) who are the trade union responsible for prison officers in the National Offender Management Service were carried out by the Pension Scheme Executive in Civil Service Pensions – Cabinet Office. The Pension Scheme Executive in 2012, held separate additional talks with the POA regarding the increase in pension age and offered a package under the Enhanced Effective Pension Age (EEPA). This provided an opportunity for staff to purchase a lower pension age, which would be subsidised by the employer. The POA membership through postal vote, rejected this offer.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T11:50:45.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506694/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506694/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Prison Officers: Retirement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on the prison service of prison officers working longer before retirement.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","33235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506695","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>During the consultation period with The Pension Scheme Executive in the Cabinet Office, the Prison Officers Association (POA) published various bulletins and communications confirming the change in pension arrangements. Additionally NOMS HR circulated communications through their internal Intranet system which is available to all staff. The intranet article directed staff to the Civil Service Pension website which held the details about the pension changes being introduced. Cabinet Office issued letters to all staff informing them of the pension changes. NOMS policy is to not issue new employment contracts or variations for routine legislation changes.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T11:54:45.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506695/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506695/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Prison Officers: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how prison officers were informed of changes to their pensions following the transfer from Classic to the Alpha Scheme; and how those changes affected the employment contracts of such prison officers.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","33239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506696","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>Prison Officers employed in the Scottish Prison Service are members of the Civil Service. All members of the Principal Civil Service Pension Scheme (PCSPS) who transitioned into the Civil Service (and Others) Pension Scheme (CSOPS, also known as alpha) were notified by letter to inform them of the change, in accordance with the Occupational and Personal Pension Schemes (Disclosure of Information) Regulations. In addition, relevant Employers were provided with a variety of communication products to inform their staff and support those who needed to make decisions. These were also held on the Civil Service Pensions website.</p><p>Between 2011 and 2015 Cabinet Office Ministers and officials held extensive discussions with all of the Civil Service unions, including the Prison Officers’ Association, on the detail of the pension reforms. There was also discussion with both the Scottish Prison Service and National Offender Management Service on the detail of the pension offer to operational staff in Prisons.</p><p>The Civil Service is a Reserved Matter and this includes pensions for all Civil Servants. Representations on the pension age of Scottish Prison Officers were made to me by the Scottish Cabinet Secretary for Justice in July last year. I replied later that month.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","33240","2016-04-19T08:44:04.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506696/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506696/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-08","Prison Officers: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department took to inform prison officers in Scotland of the transfer of Civil Service Employee Pensions from the Classic to the Alpha Scheme.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","33236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506697","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>Use of video in criminal cases provides efficiencies which benefit all criminal justice agencies, and support victims and witnesses. In particular video links allow police officers to give evidence to the court from a police station, rather than attending a courthouse, making significant savings in working hours for the police.</p><p> </p><p>The use of video within Police Forces is well established for the giving of evidence. HMCTS is also working with Police Forces to extend the use of video to applications for search warrants and other warrants.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is investing over £700m to modernise the courts and tribunals. This investment will not only mean an extension in the extent of video usage by police, but also an increase in benefits.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","33154","2016-04-18T11:46:58.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506697/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506697/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of efficiency savings made from use of video link technology in criminal cases.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","33140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506698","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>Use of video in criminal cases provides efficiencies which benefit all criminal justice agencies, and support victims and witnesses. In particular video links allow police officers to give evidence to the court from a police station, rather than attending a courthouse, making significant savings in working hours for the police.</p><p> </p><p>The use of video within Police Forces is well established for the giving of evidence. HMCTS is also working with Police Forces to extend the use of video to applications for search warrants and other warrants.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is investing over £700m to modernise the courts and tribunals. This investment will not only mean an extension in the extent of video usage by police, but also an increase in benefits.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","33140","2016-04-18T11:46:58.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506698/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506698/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Police: Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what further plans he has to extend the scope for police officers to give evidence via video link during trials.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","33154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506699","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>This Government will always ensure that we have enough prison places for those sent to us by the courts. We are investing £1.3 billion to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it even more efficient and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T14:52:39.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506699/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506699/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Prisons: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the availability of category C prison spaces in the South East.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","33153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506700","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Ministry of Justice has not had any discussions with Chief Crown Prosecutors on this matter.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on whether to charge or to prosecute individuals suspected of electoral and financial fraud in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets are matters for the Metropolitan Police and the Crown Prosecution Service. I refer my Honorable Friend to Mr. Marcus Jones’ response to Parliamentary Question 29350.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T14:29:53.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506700/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506700/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","Elections: Tower Hamlets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions his Department has had with Chief Crown Prosecutors on the decision not to prosecute any individuals for suspected electoral and financial fraud committed in Tower Hamlets during the mayoral election there in 2014.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","33188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506701","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-13","<p>Following the announcement on 3 October, the Department issued a public consultation on 25 November on changes to the regulatory framework for investments made under the local government pension scheme. The consultation proposed that guidance would be issued on how pension fund authorities should take non-financial considerations into account when making investment decisions.</p><p>The Government’s response to the consultation will be published in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-13T16:14:14.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506701/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506701/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-08","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 30 March 2016 to Question 31430, on Anti-Semitism, which legal changes form part of the Government's position on boycott, divestment and sanctions.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","33083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506702","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The information requested is commercially sensitive and, as such, will not be released. It is normal Government practice not to release commercially sensitive information.</p><p> </p><p>We hold providers rigorously to account for their performance and take action wherever they are falling short.</p><p> </p><p>Following an audit by the Ministry of Justice, South Yorkshire CRC developed an action plan. We are continuing to monitor the CRC's performance closely.</p><p> </p><p>Our probation reforms are designed to make sure almost all offenders receive support on release, including, for the first time, those sentenced to less than 12 months.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T11:41:39.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506702/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-08","South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the report of the review of the South Yorkshire Community Rehabilitation Company that took place in November 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","33118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506703","Prime Minister","false","2016-04-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Oral Statement I gave to the House on 11 April 2016, <em>Official Report</em>, column 23.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-04-14T14:04:24.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506703/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506703/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-04-08","Ministers: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether he plans to require all Ministers to publish their annual tax return.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","33189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506704","Prime Minister","false","2016-04-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the right hon. Member for Moray (Mr Robertson) during my Oral Statement on 11 April 2016, <em>Official Report</em>, columns 31-32.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-04-14T14:08:18.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506704/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506704/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-04-08","Ministers: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if he will make it his policy to revise the Ministerial Code to include an obligation on members of the Government not to use offshore tax arrangements.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","32901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506705","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p><strong> </strong>Easington constituency in County Durham is in the area covered by the North East Combined Authority and North East Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP). The Combined Authority receives annual capital allocations for Highways Maintenance and Integrated Transport and it is for the Combined Authority and Durham County Council to decide how much of this funding is spent in Easington Constituency.</p><p> </p><p>The North East LEP has been awarded Local Growth Funding for two schemes in the Easington constituency. The proposal to construct a new station at Horden has been allocated £3.3 million and the package of five junction improvements on the A1 and A19, which includes a scheme at the A19/A182 Seaham Murton Interchange, has been allocated £19.0 million.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T14:12:25.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506705/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506705/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Transport: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding has been allocated to improve local transport infrastructure in Easington constituency in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506706","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Driving examiner starters have to pass a compulsory training course in order to become fully qualified examiners. If they do not pass this course they are then dismissed. Information on starters and leavers is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Starters</p></td><td><p>Leavers</p></td><td><p>Of the leavers, those who did not pass the course</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>In the past financial year</p></td><td><p>232</p></td><td><p>152</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>In the past two financial years</p></td><td><p>389</p></td><td><p>288</p></td><td><p>28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>In the past five financial years</p></td><td><p>614</p></td><td><p>590</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:39:56.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506706/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506706/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many driving test examiners have (a) left and (b) been recruited by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency in the last (i) one, (ii) two and (iii) five years.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","32898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506707","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The maintenance of the local road network in Easington is the responsibility of Durham County Council, as local highway authority. The table below sets out how much funding the Department for Transport has allocated to the Council since 2012/13 financial year:</p><p> </p><p>£millions</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Highway Maintenance Block</strong></p></td><td><p>10.679</p></td><td><p>10.132</p></td><td><p>9.780</p></td><td><p>11.886</p></td><td><p>10.897</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Incentive Fund</strong></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N.A</p></td><td><p>0.666</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Highway Maintenance Block Top Up</strong></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>1.836</p></td><td><p>1.007</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Integrated Transport Block</strong></p></td><td><p>3.183</p></td><td><p>3.183</p></td><td><p>4.475</p></td><td><p>13.949</p></td><td><p>13.949</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Wet Weather Payments</strong></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>1.242</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Flood Recovery</strong></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>1.100</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Pothole Fund</strong></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>2.198</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>0.784</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total </strong></p></td><td><p>13.862</p></td><td><p>16.393</p></td><td><p>17.460</p></td><td><p>26.935</p></td><td><p>26.296</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Local highway authorities are able to use revenue funding for maintaining their local highways and this is allocated by the Department of Communities and Local Government through the Revenue Support Grant.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Durham County Council is part of the North East Combined Authority. From 2015/16 Integrated Transport Block Funding has been paid to the North East Combined Authority and Durham will receive a proportion of that funding.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-14T15:50:35.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506707/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506707/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Roads: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much was spent on improving the road network in the Easington constituency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506708","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>We do not hold information to this level of detail. Govia Thameslink Railways, that operates Southern Trains, might hold this data.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-18T09:28:26.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506708/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506708/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railways: Plumpton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many times Southern Trains has cancelled a scheduled stop at Plumpton Station in East Sussex in the last 12 months for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","32847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506709","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>I welcome the publication of the Office of Rail and Road's (ORR’s) recommendations following Which?'s super-complaint. It is vital that customers who suffer delays understand their rights to compensation and have access to it in a timely way. Industry must now do much more to make that process quick and user-friendly. We are already working with the Association of Train Operating Companies and the ORR to bring about improvements, and my Department will respond to the ORR’s report in the summer of 2016.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-13T13:55:23.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506709/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506709/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railways: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to respond to the Office of Rail and Road's recommendations following Which?'s super-complaint regarding train companies and the compensation process for passengers affected by train delays.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","32910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506710","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>This information is published on Network Rail’s website - <a href="http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/" target="_blank">http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/</a> - covering the years 11-12 to 14-15.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-14T14:56:02.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506710/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506710/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Southeastern","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Network Rail has paid to Southeastern trains in compensation in the last (a) 12 months, (b) three years and (d) five years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","32915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506711","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-13","<p>Details of safety events involving the transport of nuclear material both by rail and on the strategic road network can be found in the following report:</p><p> </p><p><em>Events reported to Nuclear Safety Regulator 2001-2015</em>:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://news.onr.org.uk/2016/02/events-reported-to-nuclear-safety-regulator-2001-15/" target="_blank">http://news.onr.org.uk/2016/02/events-reported-to-nuclear-safety-regulator-2001-15/</a></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","32914","2016-04-13T13:26:03.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506711/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506711/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-08","Radioactive Materials: Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what information her Department holds on the number and severity of incidents involving trains carrying nuclear material on the rail network.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506712","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Horden Station is currently being worked on by Durham City Council and is in the advanced stages of the design phase of development. The outcome of this phase will give direction to the funding requirements and delivery plans going forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:36:04.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506712/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506712/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railway Stations: Horden","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on the development of a new railway station at Horden; and when that development is expected to be completed.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506713","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-13","<p>Details of safety events involving the transport of nuclear material both by rail and on the strategic road network can be found in the following report:</p><p> </p><p><em>Events reported to Nuclear Safety Regulator 2001-2015</em>:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://news.onr.org.uk/2016/02/events-reported-to-nuclear-safety-regulator-2001-15/" target="_blank">http://news.onr.org.uk/2016/02/events-reported-to-nuclear-safety-regulator-2001-15/</a></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","32913","2016-04-13T13:26:03.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506713/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506713/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-08","Radioactive Materials: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what information her Department holds on the number and severity of incidents involving vehicles transporting nuclear material on the strategic road network.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506714","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>As part of the new franchise award, the Northern franchisee will be required before October 2017 to undertake a feasibility study, identifying options for journey time improvements across the whole network, including services in the North East. This will include possible changes to existing infrastructure, improvements to rolling stock capability and reliability and the implementing of changes to service patterns.</p><p> </p><p>Any resulting changes would be in addition to the local benefits secured as part of the franchise including the withdrawal of Pacer trains and the refurbishment of all the existing carriages retained in the franchise long term.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:20:51.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506714/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506714/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railways: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to improve journey times and train frequencies between Easington constituency and local rail hubs at Sunderland and Newcastle.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506715","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Services between Sunderland and Middlesbrough will benefit from additional morning and later evening trains. The line between Whitby and Middlesbrough (including Nunthorpe) will benefit from an earlier morning arrival from Whitby into Middlesbrough and the provision of Sunday services all year round.</p><p> </p><p>All trains on the franchise will be upgraded and fully refurbished to include improved seating, repainted interiors, Wi-Fi, real time passenger information screens and improved lighting. In addition, all the existing Pacer trains will be withdrawn by the end of 2019.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:24:31.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506715/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506715/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Nunthorpe-Sunderland Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans are in place to upgrade trains and services on the Sunderland to Nunthorpe line.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506716","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government is working closely with all northern local authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships to deliver, prioritise and develop a range of interventions for the Northern Transport Strategy, which aims to put in place a faster, more frequent and fully integrated transport system to connect up the North.</p><p> </p><p>In the short term, the £380m A1 Leeming to Barton upgrade will see the motorway connection between the North East and the five other city regions of the north completed in summer 2017. Network Rail are developing a proposal for the Transpennine Route upgrade between Stalybridge and York. Subject to final funding approvals this could be complete by the end of 2022 and would see an electrified rail line running from the North East to Leeds, Manchester and Liverpool.</p><p> </p><p>For the longer term, we are progressing plans on projects which will transform travel across the North. These include a strategic study to consider improved trans-pennine connections on the A66 and A69; the proposed Northern Powerhouse Rail east-west high-speed rail link; and Smart North, a smart ticketing system for the north of England.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:18:01.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506716/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506716/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Transport: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to improve transport connectivity between Easington constituency and the six principal city regions as part of the Northern Transport Strategy.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","32864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506717","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>When Phase One of HS2 opens in 2026, new HS2 trains will serve Manchester, north west England and Glasgow. When the full Y Network opens in 2033, the new HS2 route will extend to just south of Wigan and York and HS2 trains will then also serve Leeds, York, Newcastle and Edinburgh. The UK and Scottish Governments share an ultimate ambition for 3 hour journeys between London and Scotland’s central belt, but we recognise the further work needed to understand the benefits and business cases of different options.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T14:29:20.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506717/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506717/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the publication by HS2 Ltd, Broad options for upgraded and high speed railways to the North of England and Scotland, published in March 2016, whether the Government is planning to extend High Speed 2 beyond Manchester and Leeds.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","32807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506718","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>Her Majesty’s Coastguard does not routinely keep this information. However since January 2015, HM Coastguard has been notified of four incidents involving the use of laser pen attacks on ships in UK waters. HM Coastguard informs the police immediately so that they can consider appropriate action.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T13:40:14.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506718/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506718/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Shipping: Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many incidents of laser pen attacks were recorded on ships in UK waters in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506719","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Before these measures were introduced, the Department undertook an informal targeted consultation, which focused on key stakeholders such as national licencing associations, respected solicitors in the taxi and private hire industry and a union. The Department also conducted an impact assessment for this policy.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T10:54:26.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506719/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506719/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the likelihood of private hire operators straddling licensing authorities in order to avoid more thorough licensing requirements under the Deregulation Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","32785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506720","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>Work continues on the drafting of the Bill. Its introduction will depend on the Parliamentary timetable, but we are working towards introducing the Bill in the next session.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-13T14:34:44.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506720/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506720/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to present the new Buses Bill to Parliament.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","32814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506721","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government fully recognises the potential hazards to health and the environment that pollutant emissions from motor vehicles can cause, including when vehicle engines are left idling. Whilst the Government has not issued specific guidance on the subject of idling by bus operators, under Regulation 98 of the Road Vehicles (Construction and Use) Regulations 1986, as amended, it is an offence to cause emissions or noise by leaving a vehicle’s engine running unnecessarily whilst stationary on the road - other than when in traffic. Local authorities also have powers under the Road Traffic (Vehicle Emissions) (Fixed Penalty) (England) Regulations 2002 to issue fixed penalty notices for this offence.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving the UK’s air quality, reducing health impacts and fulfilling our legal obligations. Our air quality plan for nitrogen dioxide, published on 17 December 2015, sets out a comprehensive approach to meeting our ambition for the UK to have some of the cleanest air in the world, including by implementing a new programme of Clean Air Zones. Under the Plan, by 2020 the most polluting vehicles, including older polluting buses, will be discouraged from entering the centres of Birmingham, Leeds, Southampton, Nottingham and Derby. As part of the plan, London also has a well-developed strategy for improving air quality, including the implementation of an ultra-low emission zone by 2020 - which will cover a range of vehicles, also including buses.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T11:02:49.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506721/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506721/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Buses: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department issues guidance to bus operators on air pollution control and leaving bus engines running idle while at a bus stand.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","32801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506722","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>Network Rail and Industry are evaluating the optimal deployment options for the European Rail Traffic Management System. These will be presented to the Department for Transport toward the end of 2016.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-13T13:46:07.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506722/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506722/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","European Rail Traffic Management System","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 11 June 2015 to Question HL248, when  Network Rail is expected to complete the impact assessment of the European Rail Traffic Management System.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","32821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506723","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>An independent review of how the rail industry plans and schedules major improvement work was carried out last year. The review concluded that Christmas, Easter and bank holidays were the best times to carry out upgrades requiring major line closures, particularly in and around London where the network is busiest and access for engineers is most difficult.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail always looks to minimise the overall impact of these vital projects on passengers. As such, Network Rail and train operators are conscious that many people want to use the railway over holiday periods to reunite with their friends and families, so where possible they try to ensure the vast majority of services are kept running, as well as delivering passenger improvements on time. Network Rail will ensure around 96% of the network will be available during the next May bank holiday.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-14T14:50:02.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506723/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506723/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railways: Public Holidays","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to limit the effect that engineering works on rail lines have on travel over long bank holidays.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","32672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506724","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The contract awarded by Highways England was for a value of £422,720,000 over 15 years. This is the maximum spend allowable through this contract and includes for inflation over its duration. Other companies that bid for the contract were: –</p><p> </p><ul><li>Carillion Construction Ltd</li><li>Colas Ltd</li><li>Costain Ltd</li><li>Martin &amp; McCann Ltd</li><li>Ringway Infrastructure Services Ltd</li><li>Skanska Construction Ltd</li><li>GC Landscapes Management Ltd</li></ul><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T11:55:54.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506724/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506724/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Highways England: Amey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total cost to Highways England was of its contract with Amey for services in Area 7; and which other companies bid for that contract.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506725","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>For Area 7, Amey will report to Highways England on a monthly basis using robust bespoke performance management. This is designed to drive continuous improvement and ensure compliance with their Maintenance and Response (M&amp;R) Contract, using a combination of quantitative metrics and performance indicators.</p><p> </p><p>Amey will also be subject to an annual review and, every three years, a full Service Review will be carried out on the appropriateness of the service required and the method of payment.</p><p> </p><p>The M&amp;R Contract includes provision for early termination for poor performance. Highways England will monitor the response to poor performance and invoke appropriate action through an escalation process which includes the right for Highways England to bring in another contractor if performance is not addressed satisfactorily. Continued poor performance may lead to early termination.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T11:19:13.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506725/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506725/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Highways England: Amey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what arrangements Highways England have agreed with Amey to provide services for Area 7 of the network on (a) reporting to Highways England, (b) monitoring fulfilment of that contract and (c) options for early termination.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506726","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>We await the industry’s advice on future investment priorities for the England and Wales network in the next Control Period, building on the Wales and other Route Studies. We continue to work with the industry, the Welsh Government and local groups, including the recently announced North Wales and Mersey Dee Region Task Force, to see what more can be accomplished to deliver better journeys for passengers and freight customers in this corridor. We welcome the recent submission by the Welsh Government of their Strategic Outline Business Case for electrification from Crewe/Warrington to Holyhead as a contribution to this work.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-14T15:04:07.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506726/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506726/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Crewe-Holyhead Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of electrifying the railway line from (a) Crewe to Chester and (b) Chester to Holyhead.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","32747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506727","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Department for Transport does not delineate the average cost per mile of electrification from the wider rail upgrade works that it funds in England and Wales. The Government’s commitment to a rolling programme of electrification is reliant on a wider set of enhancement works to make journeys better. This often includes track works, gauging, signalling upgrades, power supply works and station works to allow electric trains to run. The Department does not make an estimate of the average cost per mile of electrification as the engineering complexity and challenge varies significantly across England and Wales. Electrification works in Scotland are devolved to the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p><p>However, we are aware of the significant cost to the industry and the wider public of the failure of the Labour Governments of 1997 to 2010 to progress electrification schemes across the country. This Government is determined to rectify this failure.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-14T15:07:47.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506727/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506727/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the average cost per mile of electrification of a railway line in the UK.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","32748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506728","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>No work has been done to estimate the costs of upgrading the M56 to a smart motorway between Junctions 12 and 14 as this scheme is not within the first Road Investment Strategy (RIS). Highways England is working hard to deliver the schemes set out in the RIS in the first Road Period 2015-20.</p><p> </p><p>Future investment in the strategic road network is currently being developed through Highways England’s Route Strategies process, which will be used to plan new investments in the second Road Period 2020-25.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:14:15.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506728/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506728/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","M56","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of upgrading the M56 to a smart motorway between junctions 12 and 14.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","32749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506729","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Highways England has an improvement programme to create additional network capacity by utilising the motorway hard shoulder as an additional lane. This is known as the Smart Motorway Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The cost depends on the scope and nature of each scheme and is heavily influenced by factors such as the number of junctions and the extent of work needed to existing structures.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the actual or forecast actual cost of relevant schemes started over the past five years, the total cost ranges from £7.5-£8.8m per mile of additional network capacity (using a common price base of March 2015).</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T11:09:14.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506729/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506729/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Motorways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the average cost per mile to upgrade a motorway to a smart motorway.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","32750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506730","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>Guidance from Cabinet Office indicates that there is no requirement to complete a Business Engagement Assessment on this activity.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","32742","2016-04-14T13:33:16.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506730/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506730/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether an impact assessment has been carried out on the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's Survey and Inspection Transformation Programme.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506731","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>Guidance from Cabinet Office indicates that there is no requirement to complete a Business Engagement Assessment on this activity.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","32741","2016-04-14T13:33:16.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506731/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506731/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether an impact assessment has been carried out on the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's proposals to reduce the number of marine offices in the UK.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506732","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>Brixham Marine Office, which was collocated with the Maritime and Rescue Coordination Centre, closed on 31 October 2014 when rescue coordination activity from there stopped. There were no redundancies and two members of staff relocated to other sites.</p><p> </p><p>Leith Marine Office closed on 13 May 2015. There were no redundancies and one member of staff relocated to another site.</p><p> </p><p>Newlyn Marine Office closed on 31 April 2015. There were no redundancies and one member of staff relocated to another site.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T13:46:57.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506732/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506732/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on what dates the marine offices in (a) Brixham, (b) Leith and (c) Newlyn were closed; and how many Maritime and Coastguard Agency staff were (i) made redundant or (ii) transferred to other marine offices as a result of those closures.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32743"
