 Orpington, (e) Harwich and (f) Norwich; and how many unfilled vacancies exist at each such location.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506734","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>On 14 December 2015, the Government formally announced that it accepted the Airports Commission’s case for new runway capacity in the South East, as well as the Commission’s three shortlisted schemes. We continue to consider all three schemes, including a third runway at Heathrow.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government continues to consider the large amount of very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s final report, including on flight paths, before taking any decisions on next steps. Ultimately, any proposals to alter the airport’s flightpaths would be subject to the Civil Aviation Authority’s Airspace Change Process.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-13T13:26:29.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506734/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506734/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish the proposed new flightpaths before a decision is taken on a third runway at Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506735","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>On 14 December 2015, the Government formally announced that it accepted the Airports Commission’s case for new runway capacity in the South East, as well as the Commission’s three shortlisted schemes. At the same time, it was also announced that the Department for Transport would undertake a package of further work which it anticipates will conclude over the summer. Alongside this, they would prepare an airports national policy statement as the framework for implementing decisions on airport capacity in line with the Planning Act 2008.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-13T13:30:07.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506735/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506735/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, at what stage in the decision making process regarding a third runway at Heathrow Airport he plans to bring forward legislative proposals on that matter.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506736","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>On 14 December 2015, the Government formally announced that it accepted the Airports Commission’s case for new runway capacity in the South East, as well as the Commission’s three shortlisted schemes. We continue to consider all three schemes, including a third runway at Heathrow.</p><p> </p><p>The Airports Commission published a large amount of analysis on air quality, which included an assessment of potential impacts on limit values, in its Final Report, which is available in the libraries of the House.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, as announced in December, we are testing the Airports Commission’s work on air quality against the Government’s new air quality plan, as recommended by the Environmental Audit Committee.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-13T13:35:15.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506736/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506736/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Heathrow Airport: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of a third runway at Heathrow Airport on compliance with EU Air Quality limits.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506737","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Secretary of State discusses a range of issues in his regular meetings with the Chief Executive of Highways England. I also raised the issue of litter on roads with the Chief Executive at our most recent monthly meeting on 15 March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England actively monitors local authorities to ensure standards are maintained, as it is a local responsibility to clear litter on most of the A roads on the strategic road network. On the motorways for which Highways England is responsible, more than 150,000 sacks of litter are collected every year; an average of 411 bags every day at a cost of £40 per sack.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-13T14:10:34.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506737/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506737/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Roads: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Highways Agency on litter clearance on roads.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","32709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506738","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>Under the Environmental Protection Act 1990, Highways England is responsible for litter clearance on all England’s motorways and a few selected A roads or trunk roads for specific operational reasons. Local authorities are responsible for litter on all local roads, including the vast majority A roads on the strategic road network.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England is responsible for litter clearance on all sections of the A1(M). All sections of the A1 in England are cleared by the relevant local authorities, with the exception being of a short section of the A1 from the A1(M) junction 1 to the boundary between the Borough of Hertsmere and the London Borough of Barnet.</p><p> </p><p>Litter clearance of the A1 within the Greater London Authority boundary is the responsibility of Transport for London or the relevant London Boroughs. Litter clearance of the A1 in Scotland is a matter for the devolved administration.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-13T14:15:22.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506738/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506738/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","A1: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, who is responsible for litter clearance on the A1.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","32710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506739","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>For routine highways services and specialist goods and services, Highways England has awarded several contracts that cover the whole of England. One recently awarded contract was in the Area 7, for the East Midlands and Lincolnshire:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Maintenance and Response Contract- this was awarded to Amey Highways Ltd on 14th March 2016 and is now in mobilisation.</li><li>Design Contract - this was awarded to Kier Highways on 10th March.</li></ul><p>Contracts still to be awarded include:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Construction Works Framework - Award is scheduled for early May 2016.</li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li>Salt Saturators - Award is programmed for 15th April 2016.</li><li>Salt supply – Highways England intend to use the ESPO framework which is currently being tendered for the supply of salt. ESPO is a public sector owned professional buying organisation and Highways England are scheduled to award a task order for the supply of salt in mid May 2016</li><li>Structural Inspections – award is scheduled for early June 2016.</li><li>Technical Surveys and Testing - this is the non-OJEU process and Highways England has published a Prior Information Notice (PIN) in the Official Journal for the European Union detailing how firms are to register. Responses are currently being assessed and then assessed firms will be invited to tender for specific pieces of work.</li><li>Weather forecasting – this is currently out to tender, with the award date scheduled for mid-June 2016</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Asset Led Delivery Model that is being adopted in Area 7 will also be rolled out in Areas 1 and 2 covering the South West of England and in Areas 13 covering Cumbria and Lancashire. These contracts will not be awarded until 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:00:06.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506739/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506739/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506739/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Highways England: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what contracts (a) have been agreed and (b) are still to be awarded by Highways England for (i) routine highway services and (ii) specialist goods and services.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506740","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Maintenance and Response (M&amp;R) Contractor for Area 7. Amey Highways Ltd, will be required to undertake cyclic and reactive maintenance, incident response, severe weather response and traffic management across the East Midlands and Lincolnshire. This includes :</p><p> </p><p>Cyclic and reactive maintenance:</p><ul><li>Schedule and deliver the annual programme of cyclical work to meet requirements in the most efficient and effective way</li><li>Carry out defect repairs to the requirements for each asset type</li></ul><p> </p><p>Incident Response:</p><ul><li>Attend incident, assess and advise Area 7 Control</li><li>Make safe and clear up, including environmental containment</li><li>Act as lead if other parts of the Highways England supply chain is used</li><li>Carry out associated defect repairs</li><li>Act as the on-road incident support function for Area 7</li><li>Be Principal Contractor if other contractors are used</li></ul><p> </p><p>Severe Weather Response:</p><ul><li>Provide severe weather response for winter, flooding and high winds</li><li>Work with Highways England on weather intelligence to be prepared and proactive</li><li>Provide trained driver / operatives to cover the full winter service</li><li>Maintain vehicles and equipment</li><li>Provide fuel used by fleet and management of salt</li></ul><p> </p><p>Traffic Management (TM):</p><ul><li>Provide TM for all M&amp;R cyclical work</li><li>Provide TM for all reactive work, including incidents</li><li>Provide TM for Highways England activities and Support Services, including inspections and technical survey work</li><li>Provide TM for events when requested</li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T10:59:09.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506740/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506740/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Highways England: Amey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what routine responsibilities are required of Amey by Highways England in its maintenance and response contract for the East Midlands.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32694"
