"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506742","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-13","<p>Subsidies paid from 2004 to 2008:</p><p> </p><p>2004/05 – 81.0 million (part year - December 2004 to March 2005)</p><p>2005/06 – 278.2 million</p><p>2006/07 – 168.5 million</p><p>2007/08 - 119.3 million</p><p> </p><p>Figures from 2008 onwards are published on the Office of Rail and Road’s (‘ORR’) website at: <a href="http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/95218cca-408d-4047-83ce-a542c53b59e6" target="_blank">http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/95218cca-408d-4047-83ce-a542c53b59e6</a>. 2015-16 financial information will be made available following publication of Audited Statutory Accounts.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-13T13:51:48.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506742/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506742/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Northern Rail: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much subsidy was paid to the operators of the Northern rail franchise in each financial year between December 2004 and April 2016.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","33082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506743","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>No such assessment has been made by the Department but franchisees have an obligation to minimise overcrowding. Therefore it is the Train Operating Company running the service that is responsible for what rolling stock it allocates to which service, both in type and in quantity.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-14T15:00:34.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506743/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506743/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Channel Tunnel Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the capacity and the availability of seating for passengers on peak services on High Speed 1 trains between Ebbsfleet and London St Pancras.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","33216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506744","Department of Health","false","2016-04-18","<p>In relation to the Department’s recent consultation on extending charging to overseas visitors using the National Health Service in England, a lack of available data means that it has not been possible to estimate the cost to industry of the proposal to remove the exemption from charge category for overseas visitors working on United Kingdom-registered ships. However, the proposal was included in the Impact Assessment and is thought to be small overall. <br> <br> We are currently analysing responses to the consultation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","32999","2016-04-18T10:55:34.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506744/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506744/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-08","NHS: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether an impact assessment has been undertaken of the proposal in Question 35 of his Department's consultation on the extension of charging overseas visitors and migrants using the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","33157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506745","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>This Government is providing both tools and funding to local highway authorities in England, outside London, to tackle the condition of our local road network. In the Spending Review 2015, the Government announced that we are allocating a total of £6.1 billion funding for local highways maintenance between now and 2021. This funding includes an additional £250 million between 2016 and 2021 for a potholes action fund to improve local roads, to promote innovation within the sector and to ensure that taxpayers get greater value for money.</p><p> </p><p>For Kent we are providing the following funding for local highways maintenance for the financial years 2015/16 and 2016/17:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Funding Stream</p></td><td><p>2015/16 £m</p></td><td><p>2016/17 £m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways Maintenance Block Needs Element</p></td><td><p>27.277</p></td><td><p>25.006</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways Maintenance Block Incentive Element</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1.377</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pothole Action Fund</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1.473</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>27.277</p></td><td><p>27.856</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Further details of the funding we are providing to all local highway authorities in England outside London can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/6-billion-funding-to-tackle-potholes-and-improve-local-roads" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/6-billion-funding-to-tackle-potholes-and-improve-local-roads</a></p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are able to use revenue funding for maintaining their local highways and this is allocated by the Department of Communities and Local Government through the Revenue Support Grant.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-14T15:11:34.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506745/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Roads: Kent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding his Department has allocated to Kent County Council for local road maintenance for (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","33158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506746","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>UK regulations implementing Regulation 4.1. of the Maritime Labour Convention, 2006 (MLC) make the shipowner responsible for meeting the cost of medical care for seafarers working on their ships, in order to ensure that such care is provided at no cost to the seafarer. Since the Department of Health’s proposal does not affect seafarers’ access to medical care at the point of need, no seafarers should be affected by the proposal, and there should be no impact on the welfare of seafarers. I am satisfied that the proposal in Question 35 of the Department of Health consultation is not contrary to the requirements of the Convention.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","32998","2016-04-14T14:36:14.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506746/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506746/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Shipping: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the implications for (a) seafarer welfare and (b) compliance with the Maritime Labour Convention Regulation 4.1 on medical care onboard ship and ashore of the proposal in Question 35 of the Department of Health consultation on the extension of charging overseas visitors and migrants using the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","33000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506747","Department of Health","false","2016-04-18","<p>In relation to the Department’s recent consultation on extending charging to overseas visitors using the National Health Service in England, a lack of available data means that it has not been possible to estimate the cost to industry of the proposal to remove the exemption from charge category for overseas visitors working on United Kingdom-registered ships. However, the proposal was included in the Impact Assessment and is thought to be small overall. <br> <br> We are currently analysing responses to the consultation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","33157","2016-04-18T10:55:34.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506747/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506747/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-08","NHS: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the potential cost to industry of the proposal in Question 35 of the Department for Health consultation on the extension of charging overseas visitors and migrants using the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506748","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>UK regulations implementing Regulation 4.1. of the Maritime Labour Convention, 2006 (MLC) make the shipowner responsible for meeting the cost of medical care for seafarers working on their ships, in order to ensure that such care is provided at no cost to the seafarer. Since the Department of Health’s proposal does not affect seafarers’ access to medical care at the point of need, no seafarers should be affected by the proposal, and there should be no impact on the welfare of seafarers. I am satisfied that the proposal in Question 35 of the Department of Health consultation is not contrary to the requirements of the Convention.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","33000","2016-04-14T14:36:14.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506748/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506748/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Shipping: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of seafarers that would be affected by the proposal in Question 35 of the Department for Health consultation on the extension of charging overseas visitors and migrants using the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506749","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Equality Act 2010 (Work on Ships and Hovercraft) Regulations 2011 makes clear that it is an offence to offer to pay or pay a person who is a national of an EEA State, or of a designated State (as defined in the Regulations), at a different rate based on that person’s nationality, where the seafarer is working wholly or partly in Great Britain and its adjacent waters and is working on a UK or EEA registered vessel.</p><p> </p><p>Similar legislation is applied in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T14:46:15.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Shipping: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what sanctions are in place to prevent the practice of nationality-based pay discrimination against EEA seafarers employed on (a) UK and (b) non-UK registered vessels working from UK ports.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506750","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>From the introduction of Dart Charge on 30 November 2014 to the end of March 2016 £11,212,158 in revenue has been collected from the registered keepers of foreign freight vehicles.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:09:24.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506750/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what total revenue has been generated from foreign-registered freight lorries under the Dart Charge scheme since that scheme's inception.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","32986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506751","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>From the introduction of Dart Charge on 30 November 2014 to the end of March 2016 3,392,215 Penalty Charge Notices (PCNs) have been issued for non-payment of the road user charge.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has taken a balanced approach to enforcement of Dart Charge by being clear to drivers that they need to pay the charge and giving them every opportunity to do so. As part of this approach the first PCN issued for each vehicle includes a warning letter giving the registered keeper an extra 14 days to pay their original road user charge for use of the crossing (and any additional road user charges accrued by the end of the 14 days) without penalty. In total 1,490,319 PCNs have been cancelled due to drivers paying the outstanding road user charges following receipt of a warning letter.</p><p> </p><p>In addition a further 86,195 PCNs have been cancelled following representation or appeal and 354,201 PCNs cancelled for other reasons including payment errors made by customers or early system issues which have since been addressed.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:05:22.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506751/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many penalty charge notices have been (a) issued to motorists and (b) subsequently withdrawn or successfully appealed since the inception of the Dart Charge scheme.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","32985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506752","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Department is currently rolling out the new anti-lobbying clause in its grant agreements and will monitor any feedback on the effect it may have on recipients.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T14:22:04.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506752/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Department for Transport: Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has held discussions with academics and charities in receipt of grants from his Department on the potential effect of the anti-lobbying clause on their work.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506753","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>In line with guidance provided by the Cabinet Office, the Department will monitor compliance with this clause in the same way as other contractual terms and conditions, and will consider enforcement action where necessary.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T14:25:46.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Department for Transport: Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how his Department plans to monitor and assess the effect of the revised anti-lobbying clause beyond 1 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506754","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>In 2014 the Department commissioned a value for money review of the benefits offered by an extension of Crossrail services to Ebbsfleet (via Dartford). This report recommended further analysis before an informed decision could be made. Subsequently Network Rail have launched a Kent Route Study which will assess the need for, and feasibility of, rail network enhancements across Kent. This will include any possible extension of Crossrail services which would need to be underpinned by further economic analysis conducted by Transport for London.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-18T15:45:54.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506754/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Crossrail Line: Dartford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential economic benefits of extending Crossrail to (a) Dartford and (b) Ebbsfleet stations.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","32978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506755","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The new Northern franchise will introduce at least 140 additional new DMU vehicles by the start of 2020. The new trains will be capable of operating at 100mph, be fitted with CCTV, fully air conditioned and have Wi-Fi fitted. These trains will operate on Northern Connect services including those on the Calder Valley route. In addition, over 600 existing vehicles will be fully refurbished to include improved seating, repainted interiors, Wi-fi, real time passenger information screens and improved lighting.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T09:34:26.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506755/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506755/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Calder Valley Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what provisions his Department has put in place as part of the rail franchise package for the Calder Valley rail line to improve rolling stock on that line.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","33207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506756","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government appreciates the role played by the merchant navy and recognises the need for an adequate supply of UK maritime expertise to meet the nation’s economic and strategic requirements. This includes the demand for experienced seafarers in the shore-based maritime services sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to provide support for the training of officers and ratings through the £15m Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are at the heart of the Government’s drive to give people of all ages the skills employers need to grow and compete. Maritime is a key part of this with the Maritime Trailblazer which is employer led and has one approved standard for deck ratings and a further three in development for maritime mechanic, maritime caterer and onboard services.</p><p> </p><p>The Maritime Growth Study, chaired by Lord Mountevans and published on 7 September 2015, recognised the need for more proactive action to replenish and develop the skills needed to maintain the UK position as a world-leading maritime centre. The Government has accepted the recommendations. We have already let a research contract to Oxford Economics to establish the requirement for trained seafarers in the UK. This will assist both government and industry to plan ahead and to make efforts to address priority shortages where gaps are identified. We are also working to address the other skills recommendations including conducting a review of SMarT funding, better links into schools teaching and enlarging the awareness programme to encourage entry into the merchant navy.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T14:05:46.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506756/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506756/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Merchant Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has for the future role of the merchant navy.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","33210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506757","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Since the publication of the March 2015 Northern Transport Strategy, the Government and Transport for the North have been taking forward a programme of work on an ambitious Northern Powerhouse Rail vision. Parallel work is also taking place to understand the capability of the North’s road network.</p><p> </p><p>Detailed analysis has not yet been carried out on the potential benefits of high speed rail links between particular locations across the Pennines. However the recent Budget allocated £60million to help develop the options for a High Speed 3 route between Leeds and Manchester.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:50:17.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506757/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506757/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Railways: Calder Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential economic benefits to the Calder Valley of a high speed rail link between Leeds and Manchester.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","33208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506758","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) has no direct control over recruitment into the merchant navy.</p><p> </p><p>The MCA works with strategic partners such as the Chamber of Shipping, Nautilus, the RMT and organisations such as the British Tugowners Association and National Workboat Association to encourage economic growth, including the employment of seafarers.</p><p> </p><p>The MCA also manages the Government’s Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) scheme that subsidises seafarer training by £15M annually. More than 700 new officer trainees started last year. The MCA is also involved with industry in supporting the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills apprenticeships for seafarers.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-14T13:24:57.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506758/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506758/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","Merchant Shipping: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Maritime and Coastguard Agency is taking to encourage people to join the merchant navy.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","33211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506759","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The recent Budget announced that funding had been brought forward to enable Highways England to accelerate the smart motorway investment for the M62 Junction 10 to 12 scheme by two years, and to accelerate delivery of the M62 Junction 20 to 25 smart motorway.</p><p> </p><p>Design development work on these schemes is at the very earliest stage, and as such the analysis of the full economic potential of this investment is still being developed as part of the business case.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T12:55:11.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506759/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506759/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506759/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-08","M62: Calder Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the potential economic benefits to the Calder Valley of accelerating the upgrade of the M62 to a four-lane smart motorway between junctions 20 and 25.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","33209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506760","Women and Equalities","false","2016-04-18","<p>Age is a protected characteristic in the Equality Act 2010. Where differential treatment because of age cannot be objectively justified, this will constitute unlawful age discrimination both in employment and in the provision of goods and services. Enforcement of the Act’s employment provisions is undertaken by Employment Tribunals, to which a person must make a claim if they feel that they have been discriminated against because of age.</p><p>Prior to an Employment Tribunal claim, conciliation services are provided by the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Services (Acas). According to the Employment tribunal statistics, 1,087 age discrimination claims were made to Employment Tribunals in 2014/15. 70% (761) of these claims were either withdrawn or successfully conciliated by Acas without the need for a full hearing. The Acas process is intended to enable employers and employees to resolve disputes without the need for a full Employment Tribunal hearing.</p><p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission’s enforcement powers under the Equality Act 2006 apply to age discrimination as they do to other protected characteristics.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-04-18T12:46:50.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506760/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506760/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506760/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-04-08","Age: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the enforcement of age discrimination legislation in respect of people seeking employment.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","33177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>Further details about how the Lifetime ISA will work will be announced in the autumn. Following this the Government will confirm how it will be treated for Universal Credit purposes.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-18T14:31:09.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506761/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Lifetime ISA will be included in assessments of savings under universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","33179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506762","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Government has made no such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to working to eliminate child poverty and improving life chances for children. This includes making work pay, in which the National Living Wage has an important part to play, and also through our wider reforms to support parents to move into work, increase their earnings, and keep more of what they earn.</p><p> </p><p>The National Living Wage will benefit over 1 million low paid workers this year and 2.9 million directly by 2020. The introduction of the National Living Wage will mean that a full-time worker aged 25 or over previously on the National Minimum Wage will see their annual earnings increase by £910.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-13T15:50:26.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506762/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506762/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Living Wage: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the introduction of the National Living Wage on the level of child poverty in (a) Ashfield constituency and (b) Nottinghamshire.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","33224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>The number of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claimants in August 2015 with Inflammatory Bowel Disease recorded as their main disabling condition, with a claim start date prior to 2010, in England is 340 and in Wales is 30.</p><p> </p><p>Source: DWP 100% data.</p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>Figures are rounded to the nearest 10.</li><li>The data is at August 2015, which is the latest available information.</li></ol><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-18T14:35:25.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506763/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Employment and Support Allowance: Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2016 to Question 31791, on employment and support allowance: inflammatory bowel disease, how many of those claimants started receiving employment and support allowance before 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","33135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506764","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-13","<p>The assessment for Personal Independence Payment is carried out by registered health professionals who have specialist training in assessing the impact of disability and health conditions on an individual’s functional ability, including conditions such as muscular dystrophy, neuromuscular conditions and other rare and progressive conditions.</p><p> </p><p>All health professionals receive comprehensive training in disability analysis which includes a functional evaluation as to how medical conditions such as muscular dystrophy, neuromuscular conditions and other rare and progressive conditions, and the long-term medical treatment of those conditions, affect their ability to perform day-to-day activities. Prior to carrying out an assessment they routinely refresh their knowledge of any condition with which they are not fully familiar.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s Decision Makers and Appeal Writers receive training in health conditions to assess each case individually using the evidence provided by the claimant and the Health Professional, and can call on additional support from a Health Professional as necessary.</p><p> </p><p>In all Personal Independence Payment assessments consideration is given to whether claimants can complete activities safely, to an acceptable standard, repeatedly and in a reasonable time period.</p><p> </p><p>We have also worked closely with medical experts and charities to make significant improvements to the Work Capability Assessment, including strengthening the training programme to put more emphasis on making sure that assessors do not just focus on how someone manages on a 'good day' but also consider their 'bad days' if they have a health issue that fluctuates.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-13T16:28:59.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506764/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506764/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that medical assessors and people considering appeals have sufficient knowledge of muscular dystrophy, neuromuscular conditions and other rare and progressive conditions.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","33045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506765","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-13","<p>Claimants who are found fit for work through the Work Capability Assessment and wish to appeal may be entitled to claim either Universal Credit, Income Support or Jobseeker’s Allowance during the reconsideration period. Jobcentre Plus Work Coaches work with all such claimants to tailor a package of support commensurate with their individual needs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-13T14:00:13.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506765/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506765/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department make available to people whose mandatory reconsideration and appeal takes longer than seven weeks to resolve.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","33044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506766","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>The latest available data on personal independence payment claims in payment, including by detailed medical condition, are published on Gov.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-18T15:48:52.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506766/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506766/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Personal Independence Payment: Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many stroke survivors are currently in receipt of the personal independence payment.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","33027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506767","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-18T14:20:26.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506767/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506767/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Employment and Support Allowance: Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many stroke survivors are in (a) receipt of employment and support allowance and (b) the work-related activity group.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","33028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506768","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-15","<p>The Department does not hold the information requested in parts (a),(b) and (d) of the question. In relation to part (c), the Pension Act 2014 Impact Assessment (May 2014) contains relevant information:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/311316/pensions-act-ia-annex-a-single-tier-state-pension.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/311316/pensions-act-ia-annex-a-single-tier-state-pension.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>In particular, table 5.2 shows the monthly increase in individual National Insurance contributions as a result of ending DB contracting-out, expressed in 2013/14 earnings terms on the assumption that the increased cost to the employer is passed on in full.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-15T12:13:50.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506768/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506768/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate (a) the number of employers who have passed the full increase in national insurance contributions associated with the Pensions Act 2014 on to their employees, (b) the number of employees who have been affected by those changes, (c) the change in real terms to the take-home pay of such staff as a result of those changes and (d) the number of employers who are making profits to a sufficient level that there is no need to use the override facility incorporated within that Act.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","33090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506769","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-13","<p>As confirmed by my right honourable friend the Secretary of State in his statement to the House on 21 March, the proposed changes to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) will not be going ahead.</p><p>We spend around £50bn every year on benefits alone to support people with disabilities or health conditions, with spending on PIP and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) having increased by more than £3 billion since 2010. The government is committed to talking to disabled people, their representatives, healthcare professionals and employers to ensure the welfare system works better with the health and social care systems and provides help and support to those who need it most.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-13T12:32:27.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506769/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506769/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to amend the aids and appliances descriptors, or the points awarded to them, for personal independence payments assessments.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","33055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506770","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-13","<p>Personal Independence Payment is specifically designed to ensure that the benefit is awarded to those with the greatest need and the award review process is integral to ensuring this happens. Under Disability Living Allowance over 70% of all claims had no review built-in, meaning that claimants could have been receiving too much or too little in benefit.</p><p> </p><p>We take a personalised approach to setting the length of awards, varying the frequency and format of awards and reviews depending on the individual’s needs and the likelihood of their health condition or impairment changing.</p><p> </p><p>Where the claimant has high levels of functional impairment which are only likely to increase or not improve, it is likely that the claimant will receive an enhanced rate of benefit and a longer term award.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that it is important to ensure that the review process is applied sensitively and appropriately. As such, it is likely that the awards of such claimants would also go through a less intensive review process which may not, if all the necessary information is held, include a face-to-face assessment.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-13T16:21:01.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506770/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506770/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to introduce lifetime awards for people assessed as requiring the upper personal independence payment allowance mobility component who have been diagnosed with muscle degenerative diseases or conditions.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","32963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506771","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Cabinet Office publishes information on the performance of Departments and agencies on handling correspondence from hon. Members and peers annually by way of a written statement.</p><p> </p><p>The information for the years that is available, 2013 and 2014, are in the Official Record (13 May 2014: Column 17WS and 3 Jun 2015: Column 15WS, respectively).</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-13T12:27:10.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506771/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506771/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-08","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many days it took his Department to answer hon. Members' correspondence on average in (a) 2013, (b) 2014, (c) 2015 and (d) 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","32952"
