"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486942","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-12","<p>Information on military and dual use export licences is published as Official Statistics in the quarterly and annual reports on Strategic Export Controls which are all available to view on GOV.UK. These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences.</p><p>Data covers all years from 2008 up to 30 September 2015. Information covering the period 1 October to 31 December 2015 will be published on 19 April 2016.</p><p>Bespoke reports on the published data can be run via <a href="https://www.exportcontroldb.bis.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.exportcontroldb.bis.gov.uk/</a></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-12T16:16:51.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486942/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486942/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Arms Trade: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what applications for arms export licences were rejected by his Department in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","32495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486944","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>No impact on UK productivity is anticipated. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has not withdrawn valuation services that are most relevant to small and medium sized enterprises including Enterprise Management Incentives (EMI), Company Share Option Plans (CSOP), Save As You Earn share option schemes (SAYE), Share Incentive Plans (SIP) and Employee Shareholder Status (ESS).</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has, however, announced a review of the valuation services for those schemes and is consulting interested parties.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has withdrawn valuation checks for income tax and PAYE that are not part of these recognized employee ownership schemes. Most people submitted acceptable valuations and therefore the valuation service was not seen as needed.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-14T14:06:28.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486944/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486944/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-24","Small Businesses: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the productivity of small and medium-sized businesses of the planned withdrawal of HM Revenue and Customs' evaluation check services.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","32464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486945","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-12","<p>In 2012, the previous Government asked Graeme Nuttall to advise on what more could be done to increase the number of businesses with employee ownership. The Nuttall Review identified 28 recommendations to address three main constraints: lack of awareness of the concept; lack of resources to support the model; and actual or perceived legal, tax and other regulatory barriers. The action taken to address the recommendations is explained in the ‘<em>The Nuttall Review of Employee Ownership - One Year On’</em> report published in November 2013 and available on the gov.uk website.</p><p>The Government now expects the private sector to make the business case for this model through organisations such as the Employee Ownership Association – the representative body for employee-owned businesses.</p><p>Ongoing encouragement for employee ownership is provided through four approved share schemes which have tax-advantages for both employees and employers. These are the Company Share Option Plan (CSOP), Enterprise Management Incentives (EMI), Save As You Earn (SAYE) and Share Incentive Plan (SIP) which are administered by HMRC. In 2013-14 the total value of shares and options awarded under these schemes was around £3.45bn with over £1bn of income tax and national insurance relief given.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-12T16:17:30.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486945/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486945/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Small Businesses: Employee Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he has taken to promote the take-up of employee ownership schemes by small and medium-sized businesses in each nation of the UK.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","32474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486946","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Department has not yet made final decisions on its future estate. As my right hon. Friend the Minister of State for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise has already informed the House, the current plans for the Department’s future estate are for:</p><ul><li>A combined HQ and policy centre in London</li><li>Business-facing centre, likely to be in South Wales</li><li>Institutional and Research funding centre, likely to be in Swindon, but may initially also include Bristol</li><li>Further education funding centre – location yet to be decided but may initially be in Coventry</li><li>Higher education student finance centre, initially in Glasgow and Darlington</li><li>A regulation centre likely to be in Birmingham</li><li>A combined regional footprint for where service delivery to local users need to happen on a local basis, comprising the BIS Local offices and local service delivery</li></ul>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-21T15:57:48.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486946/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486946/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, to which location he plans to relocate his Department's functions out of London.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","32477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486947","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>The due date for the rent review is 1<sup>st</sup> January 2016.</p><p>In line with standard commercial practice there are no specific plans to publish the results.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-11T14:08:53.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486947/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486947/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the rent review will take place on 1 Victoria Street; and what plans he has to publish the results of that review.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","32478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486948","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>The responsibility for running the Department, including personnel issues lies with the Permanent Secretary and the BIS Executive Board. The Permanent Secretary went to Sheffield in January to inform staff of the intention to close the Sheffield office and to answer questions. Since then, many of the Department’s Directors and Directors-General have visited the Sheffield office to discuss the proposals, answer questions and provide support to affected staff.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-11T14:09:59.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486948/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486948/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with staff at his Department's office at 2 St Paul's Place, Sheffield, since the announcement of the proposed closure of that office.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","32479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486949","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-15","<p>The Department spent £38m on upgrading IT systems in 2014-15, including both software and equipment development. This includes around £31m for internally developed software, predominantly within delivery bodies of the department such as the Student Loans Company. It also includes the Core Department roll out of a new ICT system, Evolve, for use by all staff. This replaced the previous IT service. The total cost of the Evolve rollout was £3.5 million.</p><p>The IT systems at 2 St Paul’s Place Sheffield are part of the Core Department’s IT infrastructure, so the upgrades are included in the total cost of the Evolve rollout of £3.5m. Costs were not recorded separately by location for this general upgrade to our systems.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-15T13:58:23.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486949/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486949/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on upgrading IT systems at 2 St Paul's Place, Sheffield in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","32480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486950","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-15","<p>The Department spent £38m on upgrading IT systems in 2014-15, including both software and equipment development. This includes around £31m for internally developed software, predominantly within delivery bodies of the department such as the Student Loans Company. It also includes the Core Department roll out of a new ICT system, Evolve, for use by all staff. This replaced the previous IT service. The total cost of the Evolve rollout was £3.5 million.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-15T13:59:19.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486950/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486950/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on upgrading its IT systems in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","32481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486951","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>Information on the number of National Minimum Wage enquiries made to the Pay and Work Rights Helpline (PWRH) and Acas Helpline for the ‘domiciliary care’ and ‘residential care’ sectors has never been systematically collected.</p><p> </p><p>However, additional information about a complaint is collected after it is referred to HMRC and investigated further. This can include more detailed information on the sector in which the employer in question operates.<strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-11T16:44:02.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486951/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486951/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Social Services: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2016 to Question 29835, and with reference to the Answer of 10 June 2013 to Question 158962, for what reasons information on the number of national minimum wage inquiries made to the Pay and Work Rights and Acas helplines relating to the domiciliary care and residential care sectors is not being collected at the previously available level of disaggregation.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","32490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486954","Home Office","false","2016-04-22","<p>Photographic requirements for the British passport are set out in www.gov.uk and are fully compliant with standards set by the International Civil Aviation Organisation. HMPO does not currently require passport photographs to be supplied by photographic professionals and there are no plans to change this.</p><p>The PMA is a member of the Open Identity Exchange (OIX) with whom HM Passport Office has been actively discussing our digital services to ensure open and transparent engagement with all photographic providers.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-22T10:24:36.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486954/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486954/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Passports: Photographs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will arrange a meeting between the Photo Marketing Association and the Passport Office to discuss ensuring that future digitally-supplied ID photographs meet International Civil Aviation Organisation compliance standards and are supplied by photographic professionals.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","32622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486955","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The <a href="http://legislation.gov.uk/" target="_blank">legislation.gov.uk</a> website is delivered by The National Archives and is a major online public service, visited by over two million people each month. The site provides access to legislation in a wide variety of formats. All of the content is open and freely available for access and re-use. The National Archives is committed to making the website as accessible as possible to users with visual, hearing, motor or cognitive impairments, in line with Web Content Accessibility Guidelines. There is a conformance statement at <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/accessibility" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/accessibility</a>. Braille copies of legislation as it was enacted or made are provided on request, free of charge.</p><p>Legislation changes continually. All new legislation is published on the website shortly after it is enacted or made. This year The National Archives introduced a new service level for keeping primary legislation up-to-date, applying amendments to the revised legislation within three months of the quarter in which they came into force.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-04-11T10:00:43.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486955/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486955/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-24","Legislation: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to ensure all legislation available on the legislation.gov.uk website is (a) accessible and (b) up to date.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","32555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486956","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-11","<p>An individual’s property income is subject to a separate set of tax rules to those of a private company.</p><p> </p><p>Once the changes are fully in place by 2020-21, all individuals will get finance cost relief at the basic rate of income tax, 20%. Incorporated businesses will continue to receive relief at the corporate tax rate which is currently 20% and due to fall to 17% in 2020.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-11T14:12:16.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486956/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486956/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-24","Landlords: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 2.59 of the Summer Budget 2015, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of restricting finance cost relief for landlords on the ability of private individuals who operate buy-to-let businesses with large private buy-to-let companies.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","32542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486957","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-11","<p>The most recent estimate of the Exchequer cost in 2015-16 of employee shareholder status from Income Tax and National Insurance Contribution relief is the figure published in Table 2.1 of the 2013 March Budget.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-11T13:47:59.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486957/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486957/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-24","Employee Ownership: Income Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to Table 2.1 of the March Budget 2013, what his most recent estimate is of the effect of employee shareholder status income tax measures in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","32569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486958","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>In England, revenue from the soft drinks industry levy will be used to double the PE and sport premium for primary schools, expand school breakfast clubs and support more secondary schools to offer a longer school day, including more sport. The Barnett formula will be applied to spending on these new initiatives in the normal way.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-14T14:11:29.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486958/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486958/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-24","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether revenue raised from the planned soft drink industry levy will be hypothecated for the public health budget.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","32605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486959","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>At Budget 2016, the Government announced changes to 100 percent enhanced capital allowances for energy-saving and environmentally-beneficial (water-efficient) technologies.</p><p> </p><p>Each autumn, the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) and the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra) consult manufacturers and suppliers. DECC and Defra then recommend to Treasury Ministers updates to the schemes.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the changes will be set out in Treasury Order 2001/2541 for energy and 2003/2076 for water in the next few months. As is routine, an impact assessment will be published alongside the Order.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","32572 ; 32619","2016-04-14T13:30:54.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486959/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/486959/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-24","Energy: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 2.19 of the report, Overview of Tax Legislation and Rates, published on 16 March 2016, which technologies his Department is considering (a) adding and (b) removing from the list of qualifying technologies for the first-year allowance scheme for energy-saving and environmentally-beneficial technologies.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","32618"
