"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487026","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-15","<p>Liberia has made significant progress since the end of its civil war in 2003. However, Liberia’s second Universal Periodic Review at the UN Human Rights Council in 2015, highlighted continuing concerns over gender-based violence and victims’ access to justice; the length of pre-trial detention; investigative capacity of the police and judiciary; and the death penalty. The government of Liberia accepted 147 of the 186 recommendations made. The UK Government regularly presses for concrete action in these areas through our Ambassador in Monrovia and in multilateral fora. <br> <br>The UK is concerned about inflammatory statements by the Liberian opposition in the run-up to the country’s elections in 2017. In March, our Ambassador urged the Government of Liberia to show restraint by ensuring that their responses to such statements are proportionate.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-15T14:48:29.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487026/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487026/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Liberia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the human rights situation in Liberia.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487027","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-15","<p>Liberia’s Truth and Reconciliation Commission was created in 2005 and concluded in 2010 when it presented its final report. The Government of Liberia has taken some steps to implement the recommendations of the Commission, notably launching the Strategic Roadmap for National Healing, Peacebuilding and Reconciliation in 2014. A key plank of that Roadmap has been the launch of the “Palava Hut Programme”. This draws on a traditional approach to reconciliation whereby those implicated in the civil war meet with affected communities to agree a resolution. However, obstacles to implementation of the Commission’s recommendations remain. As one of the main contributors to the UN Peacebuilding Commission’s Peace Building Fund, which funds the &quot;Palava Hut Programme&quot;, the UK will continue to press for progress on the Commission’s recommendations, including in the context of UNSC discussions.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-15T14:50:12.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487027/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487027/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Liberia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the progress on implementation of the recommendations of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Liberia.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487028","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The latest phase of UN-facilitated peace talks on Syria came to a pause in Geneva on 24 March. UN Special Envoy, Staffan de Mistura intends to reconvene the parties after the Easter break. This latest phase continued in the “proximity talks” format rather than direct talks between the parties. During their discussions with the UN Special Envoy, the High Negotiations Committee of the Syrian Opposition presented their plans for political transition. Conversely, we understand that the Syrian regime did not engage on issues of substance during their discussions with the UN Special Envoy. At the conclusion of this round of talks, the UN produced a paper outlining its assessment of the “points of convergence” between the opposition and regime and has invited both sides to consider it before talks resume on or around 10 April.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T13:08:50.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487028/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487028/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the progress made at the recent UN peace talks in Geneva on Syria.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","32556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487029","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","We are concerned about the decreasing space for civil society to operate in Egypt, including for Non Government Organisations (NGOs). Human rights defenders have been subject to measures including questioning, travel bans and judicial applications for asset freezing against individuals and their families. I refer you to the statement made by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of Sate for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood) on 22 March. UK officials have raised our concerns with representatives from the Egyptian Government in both Cairo and London.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-11T14:17:51.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487029/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487029/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Egypt: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received of human rights workers being (a) summoned for questioning, (b) banned from travelling and (c) subject to attempts to freeze their personal funds and family assets by the Egyptian authorities.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487030","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","We are aware that there are large numbers of refugees being denied access to Jordan at the Jordan/Syria border. Whilst recognising their legitimate security concerns and the need for proper vetting, we have discussed with the Government of Jordan the necessity of prioritising admittance for the sick and injured, including children. Jordan has shown remarkable generosity as host to over 630,000 registered refugees from the Syria conflict. The UK is firmly committed to supporting Jordan. We have contributed over £330 million to help Jordan since the start of the Syria crisis. As co-hosts of the Supporting Syria and the Region Conference held in London this year we helped secure over $12 billion of commitments of further support for those inside Syria and Syria’s neighbours Jordan, Lebanon and Turkey which are bearing the humanitarian weight of the crisis.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-11T14:22:29.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487030/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487030/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received of injured children trying to leave Syria being turned away at the Jordanian border.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487032","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government is concerned that elections in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) may not take place by the Constitutional deadline in November 2016. We believe that it is still technically possible to hold the elections on time and remain committed to doing what we can to support this process.</p><p>On 4 March 2016 the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for International Development, my Hon. Friend the Member for Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner (Mr Hurd), announced in Kinshasa that the UK was prepared to make available £11.4 million to support the elections provided that certain conditions were met. These conditions include the production of a credible timetable and budget for the elections.</p><p>We have called upon the Government of the DRC to ensure that political freedoms, freedom of media and speech and human rights are respected to ensure a peaceful and fair environment for the elections. We have also called upon all actors to respect the law and avoid inciting violence and disorder.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-11T14:28:53.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487032/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487032/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Democratic Republic of Congo: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of elections due to take place in November 2016 on political stability in Democratic Republic of Congo.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487034","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>We are deeply concerned by the recent violence in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories, which has had a negative impact on relations. Since the start of the current violence, Ministers and officials have spoken regularly to both the Israeli Government and the Palestinian Authority on the urgent need to de-escalate the tensions. The current violence underlines that a just and lasting resolution that ends the occupation and delivers peace for both Israelis and Palestinians is long overdue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T14:43:01.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487034/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487034/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent violence in Israel and the West Bank on relations in that region.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","32581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487035","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>We have not received any reports of Hamas fighters joining Daesh in Syria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-12T15:46:53.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487035/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487035/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Syria: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received of Hamas fighters joining ISIS in Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","32582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487036","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>We are concerned about the rise in the number of small Salafi groups in Gaza that sympathise or self-identify with Daesh. This highlights the urgent need for all the parties to reach an agreement that addresses the underlying causes of conflict in Gaza to restore security under the Palestinian Authority, and reduce the risk of radicalisation inside Gaza. We are monitoring the situation closely.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-12T15:46:13.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487036/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487036/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Gaza: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the influence of ISIS in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","32583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487037","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence monitors incidents of alleged International Humanitarian Law (IHL) violations using all available information which in turn informs our overall assessment of IHL compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of information from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations regarding reports of potential breaches of IHL.</p><p>We regularly raise the importance of compliance with IHL with the Saudi Arabian Government and other members of the military Coalition. The UK is not a member of the Saudi-led Coalition. British personnel are not involved in carrying out strikes, directing or conducting operations in Yemen or selecting targets and are not involved in the Saudi targeting decision-making process. However we have provided training and advice to Saudi Arabia to ensure continued compliance with IHL and minimise civilian casualties.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T13:07:00.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487037/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487037/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what investigatory methods his Department uses for reports of potential breaches of international humanitarian law by UK allies in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","32498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487038","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The next round of the annual UK-China Human Rights Dialogue will take place in London. The date is still being agreed with the Chinese Government.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-11T14:07:06.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487038/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487038/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","China: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects the UK-China human rights dialogue to take place.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","32521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487039","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>Over the course of the UK-China Human Rights Dialogues held in Beijing in April 2015 and in London in 2014, senior officials raised the cases of 22 Tibetans detained by the Chinese authorities. We also raised the full range of our wider human rights concerns on Tibet at each of these rounds, including allegations of torture, freedom of expression, right to a fair trial and freedom of religion or belief. A round of the Human Rights Dialogue was not held in 2013.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-11T14:59:05.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487039/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487039/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","China: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which cases of human rights violations against Tibetans he or ministerial colleagues have taken up with their Chinese counterparts in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","32522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487040","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The UK Government takes its arms export responsibilities very seriously and operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world. All export licence applications are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant factors at the time of the application. A licence will not be issued for any country, including Saudi Arabia, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the mandatory Criteria.</p><p>The Government is satisfied that extant licences for Saudi Arabia are compliant with the UK’s export licensing criteria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T13:05:29.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487040/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487040/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make it his policy to end arms exports to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","32476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487041","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>As I saw for myself, and as demonstrated my Rt Hon. Friend the member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Philip Hammond) the Foreign Secretary's visit to Islamabad and Lahore last month, the UK and Pakistan are joined by strong bonds of friendship and partnership. Our bilateral relationship is underpinned by extensive trade, investment and cultural cooperation. The UK will continue to stand beside the Government of Pakistan as it builds a more secure, prosperous and democratic future for all its citizens.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T14:55:36.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487041/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487041/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Pakistan: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of UK relations with Pakistan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","32470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487042","Department of Health","false","2016-04-15","<p>Working with the Department, Public Health England regularly undertakes an autism self assessment exercise with local authorities and their partners to gauge progress in implementing the Autism Strategy. The results of the self assessment and the individual returns from areas are made public so that organisations and people can challenge locally if they think that more needs to be done. The assessment questions and the process for local agreement are reviewed each time, taking into account that general continuity is needed in terms of measuring progress. The February meeting of the cross government Autism Programme Board considered the changes proposed for the next exercise which were put forward following discussions with representatives of Government departments, local authorities, the National Health Service, the autism third sector and people with autism and family carers. Further refinement will be undertaken over the next few weeks before the self assessment exercise is launched in the summer.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-15T13:01:22.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487042/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487042/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to (a) review and (b) improve the autism self-assessment framework.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","32469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487045","Department of Health","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre provides information on the number of nursing, midwifery and health visiting staff employed in the National Health Service in England but it does not separately identify diabetes specialist nurses.</p><p> </p><p>It is for local NHS organisations with their knowledge of the healthcare needs of their local population to invest in training for specialist skills and to deploy specialist nurses.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-04-13T10:26:17.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487045/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487045/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","Diabetes: Leicestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many diabetes specialist nurses there are in (a) Leicester General Hospital, (b) Leicester Royal Infirmary, (c) Glenfield Hospital and (d) Leicestershire.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","32483"
