"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487129","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-12","<p>Government recognises that vehicle security is a priority to ensure the safety and security of the public and their data. Government is actively engaging with the automotive industry, including vehicle manufacturers and suppliers to develop understanding and capability around the rapidly evolving cyber threats to vehicles.</p><p>As vehicle technology is advancing rapidly, particularly with respect to connectivity and automation technologies, the nature and level of threat, together with vulnerabilities and the potential impact of any successful exploit is changing. It is important that vehicles are &quot;secure by design&quot; and government is working with industry to ensure the opportunities of these new technologies can be realised safely and securely.</p><p>Connected technologies present cyber security challenges across a broad range of sectors. The recent Strategic Defence Spending Review, and the recently announced National Cyber Security Centre provide cross-cutting strategy for cyber security and it is important that automotive is considered as a part of this wider agenda.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-12T16:18:12.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487129/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487129/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Motor Vehicles: Hacking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will discuss with vehicle manufacturers improvements to in-vehicle technology to prevent vehicle hacking.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","32614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487130","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-14","<p>Increasing trade and growth through exports, to all overseas markets including Hong Kong and China is a key factor in the Government’s long-term economic plan. Government departments are working together to support UK businesses looking to take advantage of overseas opportunities and to create a strong business environment that allows them to flourish on the international stage.</p><p>The focus on China and Hong Kong is exemplified by the fact that UK Trade &amp; Investment (UKTI) has some 180 full-time equivalent posts in these markets, representing its largest overseas team working on trade and investment. UKTI also works in partnership with the China Britain Business Council (CBBC) which delivers volume trade support on its behalf for UK companies looking to export to China. CBBC offers support for UK businesses across 13 strategic locations in China.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-14T16:25:33.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487130/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487130/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Overseas Trade: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to improve trade with (a) Hong Kong and (b) China as a whole.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","32624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487131","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-28","<p>I apologise to the Rt Hon Member for the delay. The information will be deposited shortly with the most recent figures available included.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-28T16:15:31.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487131/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487131/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487131/answer/previousversion/54588","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Further Education: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2016 to Question 21634, when he plans to deposit in the Library information on the end of year budget surplus or deficit for each further education college in London in each financial year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","32658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487132","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>I apologise to the hon Member for the delay. I will reply as soon as possible.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-11T16:57:18.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487132/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487132/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to Answer Question 26990, tabled on 11 February 2016 by the hon. Member for Glasgow South West.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","32641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487133","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-12","<p>The matter is being taken forward by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) which has appointed firms to conduct an independent “skilled persons” review of RBS’s treatment of business customers in financial difficulty and the allegations of poor practice set out in Lawrence Tomlinson’s report. The review is complex and is still ongoing. The FCA expects to make an announcement about the outcome of the review later this year.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-12T16:19:52.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487133/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487133/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-24","Small Businesses: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the Government plans to publish its response to Lawrence Tomlinson's report on the lending practices of banks to small businesses.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","32662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487134","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>Government departments are fully committed to ensuring that the risks of identity fraud are minimised in transactions requiring photographs to be submitted. Currently applicants send paper photographs through the postal service. Technology now enables digital photographs to be submitted in online applications. In whichever channel is used the applicant must attest that the picture is a true likeness and departments put processes in place to assess the end-to-end risks of identity fraud. New technology has the potential to reduce fraud in this process, and we are investigating how technology can be used in a way that is both safe and cost effective.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-11T09:52:46.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487134/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487134/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-24","Proof of Identity: Photographs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions he has had with officials of the Home Office and the police on proposals to allow members of the public to take their own ID photos for official documents on their own digital devices and the potential effect of this on ID fraud and quality of images.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","32646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487135","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) has met with representatives of the professional photographic sector on six occasions since June 2015. My noble Friend the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State, the minister with responsibility for the DVLA and DVLA officials are due to meet with the Photo Marketing Association on 27 April.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-11T13:00:21.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487135/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487135/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what meetings the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) has had with the professional photographic sector since June 2015; and if he will request that the DVLA meets representatives of the Photo Marketing Association to discuss the future provision of digital ID photographs.","false","Biography information for Sir Paul Beresford","Mole Valley","Sir Paul Beresford","32647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487136","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>Cabinet Office is committed to supporting young people from all backgrounds to make positive life choices and give back to their communities. In January 2016 Home Office published Ending Gang Violence and Exploitation which sets out how Cabinet Office programmes such as NCS and Step Up to Serve provide meaningful alternatives to gangs. Over 200,000 16-17 year olds have participated in NCS since 2011 and Step Up To Serve’s #iwill campaign aims to increase the number of 10-20 year olds participating in social action by 50% by 2020. These programmes have a powerful impact on young people at a formative time in their lives.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-04-11T16:40:13.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487136/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487136/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-24","Crimes of Violence: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contribution his Department is making to Government steps to reduce the incidence of serious youth violence.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","32648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487137","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Government has made it clear that UK rates of Child Benefit should not be paid to EU children overseas. The Government paper ‘The best of both worlds: the United Kingdom’s special status in a reformed European Union’ <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502291/54284_EU_Series_No1_Web_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502291/54284_EU_Series_No1_Web_Accessible.pdf</a> sets out what was agreed at the February European Council.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-12T13:50:33.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487137/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487137/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-24","Child Benefit: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of child benefit payments to non-UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","32664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487138","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-11","<p>This information is not available.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-04-11T16:15:23.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487138/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487138/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-24","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Housing Statistical Release Right to Buy Sales October to December 2015, published on 24 March 2016, what the average length of time was from a start on site to occupancy.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","32644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487139","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-11","<p>As is the case with the existing Right to Buy, the agreement with housing associations and the National Housing Federation to extend Right to Buy discounts to housing association tenants will not apply to those people who already own a share in their home, including those who purchased their home under shared ownership.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-04-11T16:16:03.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487139/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487139/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-24","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether housing association tenants who part-buy their properties under shared ownership will be able to use Right To Buy to purchase either a share or all of that property.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","32632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487140","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-11","<p>This Government is committed to reducing youth violence. On 13 January 2016 the Home Office published the new Ending Gang Violence and Exploitation approach. This has a twin focus concerned with both reducing violence and protecting vulnerable individuals from exploitation by gangs, and how the Home Office want to work with national and local partners to respond to this.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office's Modern Crime Prevention Strategy, published on 23 March 2016, sets out a range of measures they are taking, including working with the police and industry to ensure there are effective controls on the sales of knives, particularly to under-18s. The Home Office has agreed a set of principles with major retailers and the British Retail Consortium to prevent the underage sale of knives and to ensure knives are displayed safely.</p><p> </p><p>Government is also supporting police action taken against knife crime. Most recently, in February 2016, the Home Office supported thirteen police forces who undertook coordinated action against knife crime. This involved targeting habitual knife carriers, weapon sweeps, test purchases of knives from identified retailers, and use of surrender bins.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, DCMS launched the Sport Strategy in December 2015, which sets out how sport can play a role in inclusivity and giving everyone the best chance in life.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-11T13:02:47.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487140/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487140/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-24","Crimes of Violence: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what contribution his Department is making to Government steps to reduce the incidence of serious youth violence.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","32650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487141","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-11","<p>Sir Bobby Moore OBE made an exceptional contribution to English football - his leadership and skill inspired not only the 1966 squad, but also subsequent generations of aspiring footballers at clubs across the country.</p><p> </p><p>The FA is leading commemorations of the 50th anniversary of the 1966 World Cup win, which the Government supports. The FA will be making a formal announcement in due course.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-04-11T13:08:43.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487141/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487141/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-24","Bobby Moore","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department has to commemorate the life of Bobby Moore and to mark the 60th anniversary of his captaincy of the 1966 England FIFA World Cup winning team.","false","Biography information for Damian Collins","Folkestone and Hythe","Damian Collins","32657"
